{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Colina", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Colina\n| image                     = \n{{CSS image crop\n|Image = Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac.png\n|bSize = 230\n|cWidth = 220\n|cHeight = 300\n|oTop = 00\n|oLeft = 10\n|Location=center\n}}\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_date                = 1887\n| birth_place               = [[Salamanca]], Spain\n| death_date                = 1956\n| death_place               = Salamanca, Spain\n| body_discovered           = \n| death_cause               = \n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = [[Spanish people|Spanish]]\n| citizenship               = \n| other_names               = \n| known_for                 = politician\n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| employer                  = \n| notable works             = \n| occupation                = landowner\n| years_active              = \n| home_town                 = \n| salary                    = \n| networth                  = \n| height                    = \n| weight                    = \n| title                     = \n| term                      =\n| predecessor               = \n| successor                 =\n| party                     = [[Integrism (Spain)|Integrism]], [[Carlism]]\n| opponents                 = \n| boards                    = \n| spouse                    = \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| relations                 = \n| callsign                  = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| website                   = \n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n| misc                      =\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Colina''' (1887-1956) was a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] politician. He supported the [[Traditionalism (Spain)|Traditionalist]] cause, until the early 1930s as an [[Integrism (Spain)|Integrist]] and afterwards as a [[Carlist]]. Among the former he headed the regional [[Le\u00f3n (historical region)|Le\u00f3n]] branch, among the latter he rose to nationwide executive and became one of the party leaders in the late 1930s and the 1940s. In 1931-1936 he served 2 terms in the [[Cortes Generales|Cortes]]; in 1915-1920 he was member of the [[Salamanca]] [[ayuntamiento]]. In historiography he is known mostly as representative of [[Castile (historical region)|Castilian]] ''[[Landowner|terratenientes]]''; as president of [[:es:Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria|Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria]] he tried to preserve the landowner-dominated rural regime, first opposing the [[Second Spanish Republic|Republican]] and later the [[Francoism|Francoist]] designs.\n\n==Family and youth==\n[[File:Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac.png|thumb|160px|left|[[:es:Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac|father]]]]\nThe Lamami\u00e9s originated from the [[France|French]] [[Languedoc]];<ref> ''La elegida como esposa: Eulalia Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Nicola\u00fa'', [in:] ''RamonSalasLarrazabal'' service 12.09.14, available at a WP-blocked ''WordPress'' service, 12.09.14; other sources claim the family came from Toulose, ''Etienne de La Mamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Etienne-de-La-Mamye-de-Clairac/6000000019312881943 here]</ref> Etienne La Mamye de Clairac<ref> born 1646, died 1717, ''Etienne de La Mamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Etienne-de-La-Mamye-de-Clairac/6000000019312881943 here]</ref> was a military and held high administrative posts in [[County of Flanders|Flanders]] in the late 17th century.<ref> he is referred as \u201cmariscal de campo\u201d and \u201cgobernador de Sant Omer (Flandes)\u201d, ''Claudio Diego Jacobo Lamamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Familia Lamamie de Clairac'' blogspot 16.01.10, available [http://lamamiedeclairac.blogspot.com/ here]</ref> His son arrived in Spain with [[Philip V of Spain|Felipe de Anjou]] in the 1720s and became known as Claudio Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Dubois;<ref> born 1703, died 1771; reportedly born in Toul near Meurthe-et-Moselle (Lorraine) he died in Huelva, ''Claudio Diego Jacobo Lamamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Claudio-Diego-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Dubois/6000000019301505267 here]</ref> he served on various military command posts during the following 4 decades.<ref> ''Claudio Diego Jacobo Lamamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Familia Lamamie de Clairac'' blogspot 16.01.10, available [http://lamamiedeclairac.blogspot.com/ here]</ref> Claudio\u2019 son Miguel Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Villalonga<ref> born 1748, death date unknown, ''Miguel Lamamie de Clairac y Villalonga'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Miguel-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Vilallonga/6000000019301587446 here]</ref> was the first to settle on estates granted to him near [[Salamanca Province|Salamanca]] in the late 18th century.<ref>''Ramas Espa\u00f1olas II. Lamamie de Clairac \u2013 resumindo'', [in:] ''Familia Lamamie de Clairac'' blogspot 06.01.10, available [http://lamamiedeclairac.blogspot.com/2010/01/ramas-espanolas-ii-lamamie-de-clairac.html here]</ref> His son an the grandfather of Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda, Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Tirado (1784-1847),<ref> born 1784, died 1847, ''Jose Ramon Lamamie de Clairac y Tirado'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Jose-Ramon-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Tirado/6000000019301567238 here]</ref> a military like his ancestors, fought against the French during [[Napoleonic wars]]; though he massively benefitted from [[Liberalism in Spain|liberal]] ''[[Spanish confiscation|desamortizaci\u00f3n]]'',<ref> Antonio Luis L\u00f3pez Mart\u00ednez, ''Ganader\u00edas de lidia y ganaderos: historia y econom\u00eda de los toros de lidia en Espa\u00f1a'', Sevilla 2002, {{ISBN|9788447207428}}, p. 152</ref> he turned a Carlist supporter when senile.<ref>''El Siglo Futuro'' 27.10.19, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000366219&page=2 here]; some authors note him as ancestors as \u201callegedly \u201cof French legitimist antecedents\u201d, Martin Blinkhorn, ''Carlism and Crisis in Spain 1931-1939'', Cambridge 2008, {{ISBN|9780521086349}}, p. 53. It is not clear what legitimism is mentioned, as the French ancestors arrived in Spain before the legitimist issue arose in France, while the Spanish ancestors engaged in legitimist cause were not French</ref> His son and the father of Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda, [[:es:Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac|Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Trespalacios]] (1831-1919),<ref> ''Juan Lamamie de Clairac y Trespalacios'', [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Juan-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Trespalacios/6000000019300611606 here]</ref> was among the largest provincial landowners.<ref>\u201centre los principales terratenientes y ganaderos de la provincia\u201d, Manuel Mar\u00eda Urrutia Le\u00f3n, Manuel Mar\u00eda Urrutia, ''Miguel de Unamuno desconocido'', Salamanca 2007, {{ISBN|9788478003846}}, p. 70</ref> Detained for plotting a legitimist rising,<ref> he studied law in [[University of Salamanca|Salamanca]]; in the late 1860s he served as the Carlist subcomisario regio for Salamanca province and as provincial deputy in the 1870s; arrested in 1872, he was released on word of honor and got self-exiled to France. He returned in 1874, but in line with his pledge, did not engage in further conspiracy, ''El Siglo Futuro'' 27.10.19, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000366219&page=2 here]</ref> he returned from exile in the 1870s; he then owned numerous Carlist provincial periodicals.<ref> Lamami\u00e9 founded and managed ''La Tesis'', ''La Tradici\u00f3n, La Regi\u00f3n, La Informaci\u00f3n'' and ''El Salmantino''; the first two he managed with Enrique Gil Robles and Manuel Sanchez Asensio </ref> In the 1880s Lamami\u00e9 joined the breakaway Integrist branch of Traditionalism and was its regional Le\u00f3n jef\u00e9; in 1907-1910 he served as Integrist [[Member of parliament|MP]]<ref> as a wealthy terrateniente Lamamie was in position to buy votes of his \u201ccolonos\u201d, Ros Ana Guti\u00e9rrez Lloret, ''Las elecciones de 1907 en Salamanca: un ejemplo de la movilizaci\u00f3n y confrontaci\u00f3n electoral cat\u00f3lica en la Espa\u00f1a de la Restauraci\u00f3n'', [in:] ''Studia Historica. Historia Contemporanea'' 22 (2004), p. 333</ref> in the Cortes<ref> see the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=1-1&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858870%29.NDIP. here]</ref> and entered the national party executive.<ref> along [[Juan Olaz\u00e1bal Ramery|Juan Ol\u00e1zabal]], Javier Sanz Larumbe, Marqu\u00e9s de Casa Ulloa and Juan Balanz\u00f3 y Pons, Mar\u00eda Jes\u00fas Izquierdo, ''El Sexisme a la universitat: estudi comparatiu del personal assalariat de les universitats p\u00fabliques catalanes'', Barcelona 1999, {{ISBN|9788449015731}}, p. 98</ref>\n\nFollowing childless death of his wife, in 1882 Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Trespalacios re-married<ref> ''El Siglo Futuro'' 31.10.19, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000366326&page=2 here]</ref> with Celestina de la Colina Fern\u00e1ndez-Cavada (1859-1946), the native of [[Burgos]].<ref> she was daughter to Luis Esteban de la Colina y Gonz\u00e1lez de la Riva and Felipa Fern\u00e1ndez-Cavada y Espadero </ref> The couple had at least 8 children, born when the father was in his 50s and 60s;<ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairas was short and of very meager posture; it is not clear whether it was anyhow related to advanced age of his father upon conception </ref> 4 of them died in early infancy.<ref> born between 1885 and 1894, Jacinto, Mar\u00eda del Carmen, Mar\u00eda de la Paz and Mar\u00eda de las Dolores died before reaching the teen age, ''Jacinto Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Jacinto-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000025818146636 here], ''Maria del Carmen Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-Luisa-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019359657621 here], ''Mar\u00eda de las Dolores Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-de-los-Dolores-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000025818146632 here]</ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda was born as the third son, but as his oldest brother perished and the second oldest became a religious,<ref> Juan (1886-1963) served as a chaplain Cantabria, ''Juan Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Juan-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019359657617 here]</ref> it was him who inherited the family wealth.<ref> other surviving siblings identified were Mar\u00eda Luisa (1883-1951), ''Mar\u00eda Luisa Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-Luisa-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019359657621 here], and Mar\u00eda de la Pur\u00edsima (1892-1954), ''Mar\u00eda de la Purisima Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available - [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-de-la-Pur%C3%ADsima-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/600000001935965762 here]5</ref> Some sources suggest he received early education in the Salamanca Instituto General y T\u00e9cnico,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 20.06.05, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7503899&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> others maintain that he frequented Seminario de Salamanca, then studied with \u201clos jesu\u00edtas en Comillas\u201d, and obtained bachillerato in the [[Jesuit Order|Jesuit]] [[Valladolid]] college<ref> Jes\u00fas Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez, ''Actitudes pol\u00edtico religiosas de la minor\u00eda agraria de las Cortes Constituyentes de 1931'' [PhD Universidad Complutense 1974], Madrid 2015, p. 179</ref> in or around 1905.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He then studied law in [[University of Valladolid|Valladolid]]<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 179</ref> and graduated with excellent marks in 1909;<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 09.10.09, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039895&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> some sources mention also his agricultural education.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> \n[[File:Sofia Alonso Moreno with her Lamamie de Clairac Alonso sons.jpg|thumb|wife and sons]]\nIn 1910<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 02.04.10, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5038677&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Lamami\u00e9 married a local girl, Sof\u00eda Alonso Moreno (1887-1970);<ref> ''Sof\u00eda Alonso Moreno'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Sof%C3%ADa-Alonso/6000000019299983937 here]</ref> she came from the local bourgeoisie family.<ref> her father, Tom\u00e1s Alonso del Moral, was the native of Valladolid. ''Tomas Alonso del Moral'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Tom%C3%A1s-Alonso-del-Moral/6000000019312856267 here]. He was known as \u201cconocido comerciante\u201d and member of the local ayuntamiento and other bodies, ''El Fomento de Salamanca'' 31.01.98, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5021849&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]. For her mother Aurea Moreno Brusi (1849-1937), the native of Salamanca, see ''Aurea Moreno Brusi'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Aurea-Moreno-Brusi/6000000019312856262 here]</ref> They settled at Lamami\u00e9 family estate in the Salamanca province, in-between [[Alba de Tormes]]<ref> it seems that among many estates owned, the Lamamies resided on the one named \u201cMartill\u00e1n\u201d, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 59</ref> and [[Babilafuente]].<ref> another location mentioned is San Crist\u00f3bal de Fuente, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 59; it has not been identified. Another scholar claims that the Lamamie estates were located slightly elsewhere, namely in the Martillan county, Mary Vincent, ''Catholicism in the Second Republic: Religion and Politics in Salamanca, 1930-1936'' [PhD thesis University of Oxford], Oxford 1991, p. 119</ref> Though Lamami\u00e9 is often referred in historiography as \u201crico ganadero y terrateniente\u201d<ref>Jos\u00e9 Andr\u00e9s Gallego, Ant\u00f3n M. Pazos, ''Archivo Gom\u00e1: documentos de la Guerra Civil'', vol. 9, Madrid 2001, {{ISBN|9788400084295}}, p. 411. Another scholar claims that in case of Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 the references to cattle-breeding are erroneous, see Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 179. Indeed, in the 1940s and 1950s fairly frequent press notes to toros de lidia coming from the Lamamie ganaderia referred to Leopoldo Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac, ''Imperio'' 15.08.54, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000121554&posicion=5&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> or \u201cgrande terrateniente\u201d<ref> \u00c1ngel Bahamonde, ''14 de abril. La Rep\u00fablica'', Madrid 2011, {{ISBN|9788401347764}}, p. 312</ref> it is not clear what the actual size of his estates was. Various sources claim that the couple had 9<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 179</ref> to 11<ref> ''Fallecimento Pe. Luis Lamamie de Clairac'', [in:] ''Pjicohna'' blogspot 18.02.10, available [http://pjiconha.blogspot.com/2010/03/falecimento-peluis-lamamie-de-clairac.html here]</ref> children. Raised in the very religious ambience,<ref>female children were educated by the Handmaids of the Sacred Heart, their five brothers went to the Jesuits in Madrid, Vincent 1991, p. 53; they were raised according to a very traditional model and address their father with the formal \"usted\", Vincent 1991, p. 268</ref> at least 6 of them joined religious orders;<ref> at least two daughters became nuns, Mar\u00eda Luisa and Mar\u00eda del Pilar, see Ma. Teresa Camarero-Nu\u00f1ez, ''Mi nombre nuevo, Magnificat'', Madrid 1961 </ref> some served in America,<ref> a Jesuit friar Luis died in Brazil, ''Fallecimento Pe. Luis Lamamie de Clairac'', [in:] ''Pjicohna'' blogspot 18.02.10, available [http://pjiconha.blogspot.com/2010/03/falecimento-peluis-lamamie-de-clairac.html here]; see also a YT homage to Luis, available [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Es5PCrb2cTQ here]. Also a Jesuit friar Ignacio died in Mexico, ''Agradecimiento a Dios y a vosotros'', [in:] ''Vallisoletana Dosmil'' 3 (2004), p. 3 </ref> some grew to local prominence<ref> Juan (another Jesuit) was headmaster of the Salamanca seminary, ''Juan Lamamie de Clairac Alonso SJ'', [in:] ''La Nueva Espa\u00f1a'' 28.04.16, available [https://www.lne.es/tags/juan-lamamie-de-clairac-alonso-sj.html here]</ref> and one son was killed as a [[requet\u00e9]] chaplain in 1937.<ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamamie de Clairac (1911-1937) perished during fightings in Sierra de Guadarrama in February 1937, Hermanos Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Alonso, ''Recuerdos de la guerra: Espa\u00f1a 1936-1939: vividos y relatados por los autores'', M\u00e9xico 1991, {{ISBN|9789688590317}}, p. 155, see also Ram\u00f3n Grande del Brio, ''Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamamie de Clairac y Alonso entry'', [in:] ''Real Academia de Historia'' service, available [http://dbe.rah.es/biografias/27230/jose-maria-lamamie-de-clairac-y-alonso here]</ref> The family heir Tom\u00e1s Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Alonso did not become a public figure, though he held high executive functions in [[SEAT]] and other companies.<ref> Ruth Whiteside (ed.), ''Major Financial Institutions of Europe 1994'', London 1994, {{ISBN|9789401114608}}, p. 196</ref> Neither the Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Delgado nor the Lia\u00f1o Pacheco Lamami\u00e9<ref> ''Maria del Carmen Lamamie de Clairac Alonso'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-del-Carmen-Lamamie-de-Clairac-Alonso/6000000019299764726 here]. For details on the Lia\u00f1o Pacheco y Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac offspring see Jaime de Salazar y Acha, ''Estudio hist\u00f3rico sobre una familia extreme\u00f1a, los S\u00e1nchez Arjona'', Madrid 2000, {{ISBN|9788488833013}}, p. 531</ref> grandchildren grew to prominence; the best known, Pilar Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Delgado, is a [[pediatrician]].<ref> ''Dra Pilar Lamamie de Clairac Delgado'', [in:] ''RuberInternacional'' service, available [https://www.ruberinternacional.es/es/cuadro-medico/equipos/equipo-dr-jose-casas-rivero/dra-pilar-lamamie-clairac-delgado here]</ref>\n\n==Early public activity==\n{{CSS image crop\n|Image = \u00c1ngel Herrera Oria.png\n|bSize = 200\n|cWidth = 160\n|cHeight = 240\n|oTop = 30\n|oLeft = 10\n|Location = left\n|Description = [[Angel Herrera Oria|Herrera Oria]]\n}}\nIn 1904-1906 as a teenager Lamami\u00e9 signed various open letters, usually protesting alleged official anti-Catholic measures<ref> ''El Labaro'' 04.06.06. available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5034813&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> or publicly professing Christian faith.<ref>''El Siglo Futuro'' 28.07.04, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000247041&page=1 here]; in 1905 Lamami\u00e9 asked God to allow him to become \u201ca genuinely Christian young man\u201d, ''La Basilica Teresiana'' 15.09.05, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5016931&posicion=29&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> He earned his name in history books already in 1908, when within a group of equally young 9 signatories \u2013 including [[\u00c1ngel Herrera Oria]]<ref> Jos\u00e9 Luis Orella Mart\u00ednez, ''El origen del primer catolicismo social espa\u00f1ol'', [PhD thesis] Madrid 2012, p. 42</ref> - he co-founded Asociaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica Nacional de J\u00f3venes Propagandistas,<ref>the other 7 co-founders were Luis de Aristiz\u00e1bal, Jaime Chicharro, Jos\u00e9 Fern\u00e1ndez de Henestrosa, Manuel G\u00f3mez Rold\u00e1n, Angel Herrera Oria, Jos\u00e9 de Polanco and Gerardo Requejo, Luis S\u00e1nchez Movell\u00e1n de la Riva, ''Cien a\u00f1os de la Asociaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica'', [in:] ''El Diario Monta\u00f1es'' 10.12.09, available [https://www.eldiariomontanes.es/20091210/opinion/articulos/cien-anos-asociacion-catolica-20091210.html here]</ref> later known as [[:es:Asociaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica de Propagandistas|ACNDP]].<ref> V\u00edctor Manuel Arbeloa Muru, ''La Iglesia que busc\u00f3 la concordia'', Madrid 2011, {{ISBN|9788499206363}}, p. 66</ref> Indeed in 1909-1914 he engaged in Catholic propaganda, noted e.g. when speaking at local Catholic rallies,<ref>''El Salmantino'' 03.04.09, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039857&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here], or ''El Salmantino'' 23.04.10, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5038680&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> entering committees which co-ordinated religious projects,<ref>e.g. in 1910 he entered the local junta organizadora of the project to declare social sovereignity of Christ in Spain, ''El Salmantino'' 15.11.10, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5040565&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]. The Lamamie estate hosted the first monument in Spain dedicated to Christ the King. By the 1930s it became the focus of annual processions, presided over by Jose Maria, Vincent 1991, p. 119</ref> greeting bishops,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 06.12.13, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506225&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> featuring prominently at local feasts<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 23.02.14, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507357&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> or contributing to ''El Salmantino'' daily.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 09.10.09, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039895&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Some of these engagements were increasingly flavored with \u201cpropaganda cat\u00f3lico-social\u201d.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 17.05.12, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5036628&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Some time in the 1910s Lamami\u00e9 left ACNDP, accusing them of \"betraying the Catholic cause\".<ref>the Lamamie family has even warned Jose Maria Gil Robles against joining ACNDP, Vincent 1991, p. 153</ref> \n\nIn the early 1910s Lamami\u00e9 opened his own law desk in [[Madrid]], though little is known of its activity;<ref>in 1913 Lamami\u00e9 opened the law office in Madrid which was supposed to deal with \u201ctoda clase de asuntos de Derecho, especialmente civiles, y a testamentarias\u201d, ''La Victoria'' 13.12.13, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5024204&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> he remained active in the Salamanca family [[wheat]] business.<ref>e.g. in 1912 Lamami\u00e9 enlarged family holdings by new purchases, ''El Salmantino'' 04.12.12, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039035&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> At that time he was already vice-president of the local branch of the Integrist organisation.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 12.01.11, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5036184&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the mid-1910s approaching the right-wing [[Antonio Maura|Maurista]] faction of the [[Conservative Party (Spain)|Conservatives]],<ref>e.g. during the 1915 elections Lamami\u00e9 supported a Maurista candidate, ''Libertad'' 22.03.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5022022&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> in 1915 he decided to run on the Integrist ticket<ref>''El Adelanto'' 19.11.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506135&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]; at times he was reported as a maurista, ''El Adelanto'' 18.10.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506105&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> to the [[town hall]] and was elected with no opposing candidate standing.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 15.11.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506129&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the ayuntamiento he was counted among representatives of the extreme right and one of the most intelligent [[Councillor|concejales]] at the same time.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 11.08.16, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7500494&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> As the only Integrist councilor he tended to alliance with Maurista, but also [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid|Jaimista]] members.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 04.05.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039936&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Press notes present him as an active and belligerent politician, concerned primarily with economic issues; given heavy debt burden of the city and financial problems ensuing,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 21.04.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507037&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> in 1917 he supported governmental nomination of a new [[alcalde]].<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 16.03.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507453&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the late 1910s Lamami\u00e9 already presided over work of some municipal committees.<ref>e.g. in 1917 Lamamie presiding over electoral works to renew composition of the ayuntamiento in partial elections, ''El Salmantino'' 22.12.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037996&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> He was initially supposed to run for re-election; however, for reasons which remain unclear and were probably related to failed coalition talks<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 07.02.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506740&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> he withdrew from the race and ceased as concejal in 1920.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 09.01.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506715&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref>\n[[File:Juan Olazabal.JPG|thumb|160px|[[Integrism (Spain)|Integrist]] leader [[Juan Olaz\u00e1bal Ramery|Olazabal]]]]\nAlready in the late 1910s and thanks to his connections to Integrist parliamentarians like [[Manuel Senante Martinez|Manual Senante]], Lamami\u00e9\u2019s proposals ended up at ministerial desks.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.06.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5038497&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In [[Spanish general election, 1918|1918]] he tried to enter nationwide politics himself; following in the footsteps of his father, he decided to run for the Cortes as an Integrist candidate from the district of Salamanca. In all boroughs he trashed the left-wing candidate [[Miguel de Unamuno]], but by a slight margin he was himself defeated by a Liberal [[Conde de Romanones|Romanonista]] candidate;<ref>Lamami\u00e9 gathered 4,900 votes, while his opponent collected 5,200 votes, ''El Adelanto'' 26.02.8, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506452&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here], see also ''El Adelanto'' 25.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506451&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> this did not prevent his supporters from claiming \u201ctriunfo moral\u201d.<ref>''El Salmantino'' 08.03.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037836&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here], also ''El Salmantino'' 11.03.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037838&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> In the early [[Spanish general election, 1919|elections called for 1919]] Lamami\u00e9 tried his hand again. Though he was known as councilor, local landowner, son to former deputy, Integrist, zealous Catholic propagandist and activist of local agrarian syndicates<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 18.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> he lost again; this time he was decisively defeated by a former military who ran as an independent Conservative candidate.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 02.06.19, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507751&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He was not noted as renewing his efforts in last elections of the [[Restoration (Spain)|Restoration]] era in the early 1920s;<ref>one scholar claims that \"Lamamie de Clairac had himself been sufficiently involved with the 'old' politics to be returned to the Cortes as a deputy for the city of Salamanca just before Primo's coup in May 1923\", Vincent 1991, p. 180; it is not clear what is meant here</ref> he welcomed the 1923 Primo coup enthusiastically.<ref>Vincent 1991, p. 181; the author quotes Lamamie's interview to ''El Debate'' of October 1923</ref>\n\n==In agricultural organisations==\n[[File:Jose Maria Lamamie de Clairac around the year of 1930s.jpg|left|thumb|160px|Lamamie, 1920s]]\nAlready in 1918 Lamami\u00e9 was vice-president of local Salmantine federation of agrarian syndicates.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> After death of his father the following year he inherited most of the family estates and became \u201cone of the largest landowners in the Salamanca district\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 57; also \u201cwealthy, locally powerful stockbreeder and landlord\u201d - Blinkhorn 2008, p. 53. The information about stockbreeding is incorrect </ref> Since the early 1920s he engaged heavily in works of local agricultural organisations; formally they posed as representing all rural stakeholders, but were usually dominated by landholders and adhered to the Catholic social doctrine. The key one was Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica Agr\u00edcola,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 01.03.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506759&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> renamed later to Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria Salmantina; rising to its president, since 1921 Lamami\u00e9 represented the organization in the provincial C\u00e1mara Agricola.<ref>''El Adelanto'' 28.11.21, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7508182&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here], for 1923 see ''El Adelanto'' 17.04.23, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000350025&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> In 1923 he rose beyond the province as he became one of the leaders of confederation of agrarian syndicates in the region of Le\u00f3n;<ref> ''La Correspondencia de Espa\u00f1a'' 18.10.23, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7146847&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> in 1925 it evolved into Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria de las Federaciones Castellano Leonesas.<ref>''Bolet\u00edn de Acci\u00f3n Social \u00f3rgano de la Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria Salmantina y de las instituciones promovidas por la Junta Diocesana de Acci\u00f3n Catolica-Social'' 4 (1925), available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000167060&posicion=11&presentacion=pagina here] </ref>\n\nAs representative of agrarian organizations he lobbied at various official administrative and self-governmental bodies, like Consejo Provincial de Fomento<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 01.10.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507854&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and regional institutions;<ref> ''La Victoria'' 19.07.24, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5026806&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> already a recognized personality, at official feasts at times he spoke right after the civil governor.<ref> ''La Victoria'' 10.10.25, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5026880&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In 1925 latest he was nominated ''comisario regio de fomento'', a provincial delegate of [[Ministry of Development (Spain)|Ministry of Infrastructure]];<ref>''El Adelanto'' 16.12.25, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000350844&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]; Lamamie served as comisario regio de fomento and head of Consejo Provincial de Fomento at least until 1928, ''El Adelanto'' 24.01.28, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351495&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> the same year he grew to president of Federaci\u00f3n de Sindicatos Cat\u00f3licos.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 16.12.25, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000350844&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In 1927 Lamami\u00e9 was in executive of Uni\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico Agraria Castellano Leonesa; he tried to endorse its vision of rural regime<ref>it included regulation of rental contracts and advanced a theory named \u201csocialismo agrario\u201d, ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 09.02.27, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201441&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> and took part in Congreso Nacional Cerealista;<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 06.09.27, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351376&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here], also Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 60</ref> also during following years he used to give lectures on organisation of agricultural labor.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 19.10.29, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000352035&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the late 1920s he focused on presidency of Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico Agraria Salmantina and activity in Acci\u00f3n Social Cat\u00f3lico Agraria.<ref> ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 26.05.28, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2206547&posicion=5&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He formed part of Comis\u00edon Trigueroharinaria within Comisi\u00f3n Arbitral Agr\u00edcola, a [[Miguel Primo de Rivera|primoderiverista]] arbitration committee supervised by Ministry of Agriculture,<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 180</ref> and was member of C\u00e1mara de la Propiedad R\u00fastica.<ref>''Bolet\u00edn de Acci\u00f3n Social \u00f3rgano de la Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria Salmantina y de las instituciones promovidas por la Junta Diocesana de Acci\u00f3n Catolica-Social'' 11 (1929), available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000167186&posicion=22&presentacion=pagina here]. One scholar claims that \"Proprietors of Rural Estates\" organization - not sure whether same as C\u00e1mara de la Propiedad R\u00fastica - was founded \"in response to the Republic's plans for agrarian reform\", Vincent 1991, p. 167 </ref> He grew to vice-president of Confederaci\u00f3n Hidrogr\u00e1fica del Duero,<ref>''Diario de Burgos'' 31.01.29, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000443371&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]; the company was active at least since 1926, ''El Adelanto'' 19.12.26, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351156&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> but scaled down his activity as a lawyer.<ref> in 1928 Lamamie ceased as member of Junta de Gobierno of the Salamanca colegio de abogados, ''El Adelanto'' 25.05.28, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351598&posicion=6&presentacion=pagina here]</ref>\n[[File:Castroj3.JPG|thumb|wheat fields, [[Castile (historical region)|Castile]]]]\nFollowing the fall of [[Miguel Primo de Rivera|Primo]] Lamami\u00e9 assumed more militant political stand; in 1930 he agonized about \u201cgrave situation in agriculture\u201d<ref> ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 02.05.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201729&posicion=12&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and demanded permanent consultative representation of landowners\u2019 federations in Madrid;<ref> ''El Dia de Palencia'' 14.04.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201716&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> indeed he was shortly nominated member of Consejo del Economia Nacional.<ref> ''Las Provincias'' 16.12.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000320247&posicion=6&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> On first pages he claimed that rural syndicates did not intend to engage in politics,<ref>Vincent 1991, p. 183</ref> but on the other hand when representing \u201clabrador castellano\u201d they looked beyond purely agricultural interest.<ref>''El Dia de Palencia'' 13.05.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201738&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]; for another huge front-page interview see ''El Dia de Palencia'' 30.05.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201752&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> In June he co-founded Acci\u00f3n Castellana,<ref>its flag was that of the fatherland and \"Religion, Family, Order, Property and Monarchy\" slogan, Vincent 1991, p. 179</ref> supposed to promote \u201caspiraciones nacionales y agrarias\u201d,<ref> ''Mir\u00f3briga'' 29.06.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000166113&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> though he also appeared on meetings of Partido Provincial Agrario.<ref> ''El Dia de Palencia'' 10.10.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2205178&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He called to do away with ruling corrupted oligarchies,<ref>one scholar claims Lamamie was part of the primoderiverista oligarchy himself as Salamanca's representative \"in the dictator's National Assembly\", Vincent 1991, p. 181. There is no confirmation of his place in Asamblea Nacional Consultiva, and the official Cortes service does not list him (or any other Lamamie) as such</ref> but opposed the rising republican tide by lambasting \u201cfalse liberties and democratic absurdities\u201d;<ref>in March 1931 Lamami\u00e9 demanded also derogation of penal code adopted during the dictatorship, ''El Adelanto'' 05.03.31, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000352460&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> according to his vision, [[Castile (historical region)|Castile]] as the heart of Spain remembered that \u201cen primer t\u00e9rmino Dios\u201d.<ref> Jaume Claret Miranda, ''Esta salvaje pesadilla: Salamanca en la Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola'', Salamanca 2007, {{ISBN|9788484329015}}, p. 9</ref> In September he declared running to the future Cortes in name of Sindicatos Cat\u00f3licos Agrarios,<ref> ''Heraldo Alaves'' 06.09.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000030524&posicion=6&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> but in February 1931 specified he would rather stand in name of Acci\u00f3n Castellana.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 13.02.31, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000352443&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In April 1931 he was elected president of [[:es:Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria|Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria]], the nationwide agricultural organization.<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 180</ref>\n\n==Republic: in Cortes==\n{{CSS image crop\n|Image = Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac.jpg\n|bSize = 220\n|cWidth = 160\n|cHeight = 240\n|oTop = 30\n|oLeft = 40\n|Location = left\n|Description = Lamamie, 1930s\n}}\nAs representative of Acci\u00f3n Castellana Lamami\u00e9 joined a [[Electoral Carlism (Second Republic)|general right-wing alliance]]<ref> Acci\u00f3n Castellano was a satelite of Acci\u00f3n Nacional, the latter generally dominated by the Alfonsinos and accidentalists; Integrist presence in the organisation was a bit of an exception, Antonio M. Moral Roncal, ''La cuesti\u00f3n religiosa en la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola: Iglesia y carlismo'', Madrid 2009, {{ISBN|9788497429054}}, p. 50; similar comments in Vincent 1991, p. 191</ref> and was comfortably elected to the [[Spanish general election, 1931|first Republican Cortes]] from his Salamanca.<ref> see the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=1-1&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. here]</ref> In the chamber he joined the [[Spanish Agrarian Party|Agrarian block]];<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 126; one author claims that the Agrarian block \"distilled old monarchist wine into new republican bottles\", Vincent 1991, p. 221</ref> with 2 other Integrists<ref> dubbed \u201cintegrist trio\u201d; its other members were [[Francisco Est\u00e9vanez Rodr\u00edguez|Est\u00e9vanez Rodr\u00edguez]] and [[Ricardo G\u00f3mez Roji|G\u00f3mez Roji]], Blinkhorn 2008, p. 56</ref> he formed the right-wing<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 189</ref> or \u201cextreme right-wing\u201d of the grouping.<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 217</ref> As a Carlist he was re-elected from Salamanca<ref> initially Lamamie was supposed to run in the 1933 elections from Barcelona, Robert Vallverd\u00fa i Mart\u00ed, ''El carlisme catal\u00e0 durant la Segona Rep\u00fablica Espanyola 1931-1936'', Barcelona 2008, {{ISBN|9788478260805}}, p. 146</ref> in [[Spanish general election, 1933|1933]]<ref> see the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=2-2&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. here]</ref> and [[Spanish general election, 1936|1936]]; in the latter case the ticket was annulled<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 289; see also the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=3-3&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. here]</ref> with his engagement in negotiation of government grain contracts quoted as incompatible with electoral law.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 231</ref> The 5 years spend in the Cortes marked the climax of Lamami\u00e9\u2019s career; though member of minor groupings, he became a nationally recognizable figure due to his oratory skills, vehemence and engagement in heated plenary debates. His parliamentary career was marked by two threads: opposition to republican agrarian policy and opposition to advanced secular format of the state.\n\nLamami\u00e9<ref> allegedly with Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Gil Robles Lamamie was one of \u201cdos personajes de enorme relevancia en el campo pol\u00edtico conservador\u201d in the province; Blinkhorn 2008, p. 65</ref> \u201cemerged as the most ardent Catholic opponent of state interference with the distribution of landed property\u201d<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 65</ref> and did his best to block the agrarian reform;<ref> Francisco Javier Lamb\u00e1n Monta\u00f1\u00e9s, ''La reforma agraria republicana en Arag\u00f3n, 1931-1936'' [PhD Universidad de Zaragoza], Zaragoza 2014, p. 74</ref> some count him among \u201cdefensores a ultranza de las viejas estructuras territoriales\u201d.<ref> opinion of Manuel Tu\u00f1on de Lara, ''Objectivo: acabar con la Rep\u00fablica'', [in:] ''SBHAC'' service, available [http://www.sbhac.net/Republica/TextosIm/Otros/Conspiracion/Conspiracion.htm here] </ref> Though Lamami\u00e9 recognized the need to sanate the rural regime following \u201ca century of rural liberalism\u201d, he thought the republican law an over-reaction, \u201can even worse doctrine which converts us all into slaves of the state\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 79</ref> Especially in 1933-1935 he labored to loosen already adopted rural regulations like the law on [[:es:Primer bienio de la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola|jurados mixtos]] or the Rural Lease Act.<ref> Sergio Riesco Roche, ''La lucha por la tierra: reformismo agrario y cuesti\u00f3n yuntera en la provincia de C\u00e1ceres'' [PhD thesis Complutense], Madrid 2005, p. 340</ref> Though he lambasted alleged ''[[Etatism|etatisme]]'' of [[Manuel Gim\u00e9nez Fern\u00e1ndez|Gim\u00e9nez Fern\u00e1ndez]],<ref> Lamami\u00e9 vehemently opposed cutting down minimum prices of wheat and blamed speculators, not producers, for high market prices </ref> at times he swallowed his \u201cdislike of state intervention\u201d and demanded governmental assistance by purchases of wheat surplus.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 195</ref> Lamami\u00e9 gained notoriety when left-wing newspapers quoted his declaration that he would turn a [[Schismatic (religion)|schismatic]] rather than accept land reform in case it gets supported by the Church;<ref> his alleged statement which made rounds across all Spain was that \u201csi not quitan las tierras, nos haremos cism\u00e1ticos\u201d; another version is that when told that \"habr\u00eda que poner en marcha medidas en el agro que siguieran la doctrina social de la Iglesia\", Lamami\u00e9 replied that \"antes se hac\u00eda cism\u00e1tico\", both versions repeated after Lamb\u00e1n Monta\u00f1\u00e9s 2014</ref> the claim is referred in literature as a proof of Lamami\u00e9\u2019s hypocrisy,<ref> Lamb\u00e1n Monta\u00f1\u00e9s 2014, p. 74</ref> but some claim it was fabricated by hostile propaganda.<ref>V\u00edctor Manuel Arbeloa Muru, ''\u201eSi nos quitan las tierras, not haremos cism\u00e1ticos\u201d'', [in:] ''Preg\u00f3n'' 53 (2019), pp. 34-35</ref> The member of radical right-wing among the Agrarians, also among the Carlists he stood as \u201clast-ditch defender of property\u201d<ref> though Lamamie is usually presented as fierce opponent of Republican agrarian reform, he was equally hostile versus the rural regime as endorsed by syndicalist revolutionaries of the Falange, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 124</ref> against left-leaning party parliamentarians like Gin\u00e9s Martinez Rubio.<ref> G\u00ednes Mart\u00ednez is presented with some irony \u2013 perhaps aimed to question sincerity of his zeal \u2013 as \u201cproletarian hammer of the selfish capitalist\u201d, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 124. One scholar claims, however, that politicians like Lamamie \"posed effectively as the true defenders of the people\", Vincent 1991, p. 355</ref>\n[[File:Congreso de los Diputados (Espa\u00f1a) 15.jpg|thumb|parliament building (present view)]]\nAnother major focus of Lamami\u00e9 as a deputy were religious issues.<ref>the Lamamie family was zealously Catholic. During the Republic days, when religious public rallies were generally illegal save for specific permits, on the private Lamamie estate they organized pilgrimages and romerias, at times attracting thousands of attendees, Vincent 1991, p. 134. The author mentions a \"Juan Lamamie\" as organizer</ref> He vehemently supported confessionality of state and claimed that \u201cGod comes first, and not merely relegated to the privacy of conscience\u201d.<ref>\u201clo primero es Dios, pero no relegado a la intimidad de la conciencia, como ahora es modo sostener, sino a quien no concebimos sino informandolo todo: el individuo, la familia, la sociedad, las costumbres, las leyes, la moral y el derecho\u201d, quoted after Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 270</ref> During the constitutional debate of 1931 he ardently opposed stipulations he considered oppressive and unjust versus the Catholics,<ref>\"within the Cortes and such unlikely champions of democracy as Lamamie de Clairac and Gil Robles, together with their fell ow Agrarians, the priest-deputies Gomez Rojf and Molina Nieto, were to be heard speaking the language of liberty, equality and civil rights\", Vincent 1991, pp. 239-240</ref> warning that if the state turns against them, they \u201cshall have no other remedy than to move against the Republic\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 66, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 54. Reportedly that was \"at the instigation of Lamamie\" that the Agrarians, the Traditionalists and the Basques withdrew from the Cortes in protest during voting on the constitutional draft, Vincent 1991, p. 242</ref> Lamami\u00e9 dedicated not one of his harangues to defend the Jesuits, the order marked for forcible dissolution; he tried to dismantle the republican narrative of the famous Jesuit \u201cfourth vow\u201d<ref> Lamamie claimed that only some 25% of the Jesuits took the famous \u201cfourth vow\u201d of obedience to the pope, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 78</ref> and lambasted the draft not only as inhuman, but also as non-constitutional;<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 61</ref> his campaign<ref>reinforced by ''La Gaceta Regional'', a Salamanca daily purchased in 1932 by a consortium of local businessmen, led by Lamamie, Vincent 1991, p. 156</ref> lasted until 1933, but proved fruitless.<ref> in May 1933 Lamamie unleashed his fury against the draft of the Law on Congregations; he declared it as aimed against God and openly claimed that it should be disobeyed, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 104</ref> Numerous timed denied the right to speak,<ref> e.g. in 1932 the speaker did not allow Lamamie to take to the floor and speak in defence of the Jesuits. He found an unexpected ally in the person of Miguel de Unamuno, who came to his help and claimed he had the right to speak, Alfonso Carlos Saiz Valdivielso, ''Don Miguel de Unamuno, un disidente ante las Cortes Constituyentes de la Segunda Rep\u00fablica'', [in:] ''Estudios de Deusto'' 51/1 (2003), p. 333</ref> he later got his parliamentary addresses published as a booklet.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 62</ref> During the [[:es:Segundo bienio de la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola|1933-1936 term]], dominated by the Right, he demanded nothing less than derogation of the constitutional article which defined the Republic as a secular state.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 180</ref>\n\n==Republic: in Carlist executive==\n[[File:M\u00edting del del Cercle Tradicionalista.jpeg|thumb|left|Carlist gathering, 1930s]]\nLamami\u00e9 entered the Republican parliament as an Integrist associated with Salamantine agrarian and generic right-wing circles,<ref> e.g. during the 1931 electoral campaign he toured the Salamanca province with Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Gil Robles, then rather unknown aspiring right-wing politician, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 100</ref> but already in late 1931 he was at odds with local conservatives.<ref> already in November 1931 Lamami\u00e9 was at odds with local conservatives; despite his position of the local parliamentarian he did not speak at their rallies. Background of the conflict is not entirely clear; apart from controversies related to reportedly appeasing conservative stand versus the Republic there might have been personal issues involved, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 53</ref> Instead, like most Integrists he started to approach the Carlists<ref>one scholar names Lamamie \"lifelong supporter of the Carlist pretender to the throne\", Vincent 1991, p. 180. However, there is no information available on his support for the Carlist claim prior to 1931</ref> and was leaning towards reunification of all Traditionalist branches.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 73</ref> The project was complete in early 1932, when they merged in [[Traditionalist Communion|Comuni\u00f3n Tradicionalista]].<ref>it seems that though member of the Carlist organization, until dissolution of the Cortes in 1933 he used to form part of the Agrarian minority, Vincent 1991, p. 234</ref> Within the organisation Lamami\u00e9 entered its nationwide executive Junta Suprema and became secretary of the body;<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, pp. 77-78</ref> he was also double-hatting as regional Traditionalist jef\u00e9 in Le\u00f3n.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 79</ref> In 1933 latest he was put in charge of the propaganda section<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 70</ref> and reportedly contributed to change of Carlist image; the movement was no longer perceived as antiquated group of senile veterans but as a dynamic organization of young militants.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 83</ref> Though at times speaking at public rallies,<ref> despite his role in the Carlist nationwide executive Lamami\u00e9 fairly rarely spoke on public rallies beyond his native Old Castile; one of such cases was the spring 1932 campaign in Catalonia, Vallverdu i Marti 2008, p. 101, C\u00e9sar Alcal\u00e1, ''D. Mauricio de Sivatte. Una biograf\u00eda pol\u00edtica (1901-1980)'', Barcelona 2001, {{ISBN|8493109797}}, p. 20</ref> he turned into \u201cthe most persuasive and accomplished Carlist orator\u201d in the Cortes.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 78</ref> He went well with older generation of leaders, especially the fellow landowner [[Tomas Dominguez Arevalo|Rodezno]], and following re-organisation of 1934 he entered not only the broad Junta Suprema Nacional, but also a much smaller governing body, Junta Delegada.<ref> Junta Delegada consisted of Rodezno, [[Victor Pradera Larumbe|Pradera]], Lamami\u00e9 and [[Jose Luis de Oriol y Uriguen|Oriol]], Blinkhorn 2008, p. 133, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 117</ref>\n\nAlready in the early 1930s Lamami\u00e9 worked with the fellow Integrist [[Manuel Fal Conde|Manuel Fal]]<ref>[Ana Mar\u00edn Fidalgo, Manuel M. Burgue\u00f1o], ''In memoriam. Manuel J. Fal Conde (1894-1975)'', Sevilla 1978, p. 25</ref> and reportedly claimed the latter would one day become the party leader.<ref> ''Pensamiento Alaves'' 25.01.38, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000035336&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Following growing disappointment with Rodezno\u2019s lead, in 1934 he and Manuel Senante floated the candidacy of Fal,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 137</ref> who indeed assumed the party jefatura. Under his command Lamami\u00e9 retained his position as head of propaganda<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 207, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 120; in line with his propaganda tasks, in 1935 co-ordinated activities of the Carlist press, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 275</ref> and in 1935 was nominated to Council of the Communion, an advisory body supposed to assist Fal.<ref> the Council consisted of [[Esteban Bilbao Egu\u00eda|Bilbao]], [[Luis Hernando de Larramendi y Ruiz|Larramendi]], [[Lorenzo Alier Cassi|Alier]], Senante and Lamamie, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 215, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 263</ref> Since the mid-1930s he was gradually replacing Rodezno as the Carlist parliamentary leader. In the party he was one of the central figures who \u201ccould be relied upon to bridge the gap between the Communion old and new establishments\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 229-230</ref>\n[[File:Mitin tradicionalista.jpeg|thumb|Lamami\u00e9 at Carlist rally, 1930s (1fL)]]\nThough some scholars admit that initially Lamami\u00e9 might have been willing to collaborate with the Republican authorities,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 60</ref> adopted \u201cuna postura suave y conciliadora\u201d and only after 1933 turned into \u201cintegrista furibundo\u201d,<ref> J. M. Castells, ''Las asociaciones religiosas en la Espa\u00f1a contemporanea'', Madrid 1973, p. 394</ref> they note that it did not take long before he started to view the Republic as a tyrannical regime<ref> in the aftermath of sanurjada and in midsts of ensuing governmental repressions Lamami\u00e9 \u201cwas typical in belabouring the government for stepping up its \u2018tyrannical\u2019 behaviour by means of indiscriminate arrests, suspensions, closures, expropriations and deportations\u201d, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 93</ref> to be toppled sooner or later.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 66, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 54 </ref> He considered democracy incompatible with \"people's rights\".<ref>\"la democracia pol\u00edtica es la negaci\u00f3n efectiva de los derechos del pueblo\", quoted after Mar\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n Marcos del Olmo, ''Cultura de la violencia y Parlamento: los diputados Castellanos y Leoneses en las Cortes de 1936'', [in:] ''Diacronie'' 7 (2011), p. 9 </ref> Since late 1931 he was increasingly critical of right-wing politics guided by the \u201clesser evil\u201d principle and hence abandoned Acci\u00f3n Castellana in late 1932.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 101-102</ref> Since then he scorned [[CEDA]] for illusions about rectifying the Republic<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 129-130</ref> and in 1934 claimed that the CEDA-backed government<ref> in late 1932 and early 1933 Lamami\u00e9 declared that Carlism would never collaborate with any republican government, this is neither with a right-wing one, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 103</ref> gave in to [[Alejandro Lerroux|Lerroux]] and the Left.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 187. During the tenure of the right-wing government Lamamie was fully aware and approving of few Carlist militants being sent to Rome to receive military training with a view of a future violent overthrow of the Republic, Vincent 1991, p. 297</ref> In 1935 he engaged in virulent press polemics with his former prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Jose Maria Gil Robles Quinones|Gil Robles]]<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 192</ref> and was denounced by ''[[El Debate]]'' as running against the papal teaching;<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 153</ref> in spite of it, in 1936 he half-heartedly assisted Fal in attempt to mount a right-wing electoral alliance.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 203</ref> While hostile to ''cedistas'' he was moderately<ref> in 1933 Lamamie was not very enthusiastic about a close co-operation with [[Renovaci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola]]; if so, it was to serve very limtied, pragmatic, electoral ends and in no way should it amount to any firm alliance, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 109</ref> in favor of a generic monarchist alliance within National Bloque.<ref> historiographic accounts tend to differ. One scholar counts Lamami\u00e9 among farily enthusiastic supporters of Bloque Nacional, see Blinkhorn 2008, p. 189; others are less definite, see Moral Roncal 2009, p. 125</ref> As former Integrist he was not outspoken on dynastical issues,<ref> e.g. in 1931 the Traditionalists were bewildered about a so-called Pact of Territet, an informal dynastical agreement allegedly sealed by Alfonso XIII and Don Jaime; it is difficult to tell from the accounts available what the position of Lamami\u00e9 was, Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 72, 322</ref> though he stayed fully within limits of the Carlist loyalty.<ref> one of the rare cases when Lamami\u00e9 engaged in dynastical propaganda during the Republc era was his co-edition of a 1935 document, signed by a few Carlist leaders. Following the wedding of the Alfonsist infant Don Juan, the document denied any rights to the throne either to Don Juan or to his future offspring, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 208</ref>\n\n==Conspirator and rebel==\n[[File:Jose Maria Lamamie de Clairac y Alonso.jpg|thumb|160px|left|son as [[requet\u00e9]]<ref>blown up by a grenade during fightings in Sierra de Guadarrama in February 1937. Four months earlier, his father called upon the young men to \"sacrifice your lives on the altar of ... traditional Spain\", quoted after Vincent 1991, pp. 348-349</ref>]]\nSince the electoral triumph of [[Popular Front (Spain)|Popular Front]] in February 1936 Lamami\u00e9 was increasingly perplexed about perceived revolutionary tide and inclined towards mounting a counter-action. In the early spring he \u201cnursed a longing for a purely Carlist rising\u201d,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 238</ref> prepared but eventually abandoned by the Comuni\u00f3n executive. However, he remained heavily engaged in conspiracy;<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 296, Jordi Canal, ''El carlismo. Dos siglos de contrarrevoluci\u00f3n en Espa\u00f1a'', Madrid 2000, {{ISBN|9788420639475}}, p. 324</ref> together with dynastical representative [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Don Javier]] and Manuel Fal he formed a triumvirate which co-ordinated works of all sections of the organization.<ref> Juan Carlos Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo de Quir\u00f3s, ''El Carlismo, la Rep\u00fablica y la Guerra Civil (1936-1937). De la conspiraci\u00f3n a la unificaci\u00f3n'', Madrid 1996, {{ISBN|8487863523}}, p. 19; Julio Ar\u00f3stegui, ''Combatientes Requet\u00e9s en la Guerra Civil espa\u00f1ola, 1936-1939'', Madrid 2013, {{ISBN|9788499709758}}, p. 99</ref> Though he did not speak with military conspirators, he negotiated with Gil Robles; as late as on July 12 in [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]] the two fruitlessly discussed CEDA\u2019s access to the [[Spanish coup of July 1936|coup]].<ref> Ar\u00f3stegui 2013, p. 117</ref> It is not clear where Lamami\u00e9 resided on July 18-19, yet it is known that his wife and some sons remained in Madrid.<ref> Lamami\u00e9\u2019s wife and children trapped in Madrid following some time found refuge in foreign diplomatic missions and eventually made it to the Nationalist zone; for recollections of verious members of the Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac family, including these residing in Madrid, see Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Alonso 1991, pp. 19-101</ref>\n\nOn July 26 Lamami\u00e9 delivered an address broadcast by the Burgos radio;<ref> ''Heraldo de Zamora'' 27.07.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2257365&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> he called to support \"sacrosant crusade\" against \"horde of evil-doers at the service of Russia\".<ref>Vincent 1991, p. 343, though it is not sure whether the phrases quoted were not broadcast during a later, August Lamamie speech</ref> In response his Madrid bank account was seized<ref> ''La Libertad'' 20.08.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000201979&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and Republican press claimed a [[machine gun]] and loads of ammunition had been found in his [[safety deposit box]].<ref> ''Heraldo de Castell\u00f3n'' 20.08.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000384168&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> During August he toured various cities in Northern Castile encouraging recruitment<ref> ''Pensamiento Alaves'' 08.08.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000033664&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and visiting requet\u00e9 units.<ref> Ar\u00f3stegui 2013, p. 632</ref> In September he entered the newly formed wartime party executive Junta Nacional Carlista de Guerra as its secretary.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 22</ref> With his office based in Burgos, Lamami\u00e9 was also entrusted with recruitment and deployment of requet\u00e9.<ref> Ar\u00f3stegui 2013, p. 647</ref> He seemed to have stood in-between Fal Conde and somewhat autonomous [[Navarre|Navarrese]] command, Junta Central Carlista. Some authors claim he was among Fal\u2019s less dependable trustees,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 269</ref> though this enabled him to engage in some fence-mending between the two Carlist Juntas.<ref> e.g. in early December 1936, following Fal Conde\u2019s decision to set a Carlist-only military academy, Lamami\u00e9 travalled to Pamplona to discuss with the local executive the details of setting up and the institution and organizing its teaching staff; one historian views the move as sort of an olive branch offered to the Navarrese Junta by Fal and the central Junta, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 237</ref> When Fal was forced to go on exile the power in the party technically rested with [[Jose Maria Valiente Soriano|Valiente]] and Lamami\u00e9, though in fact it slipped to traditional leaders from Navarre and the [[Names of the Basque Country (in Spanish)|Vascongadas]].<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 278</ref> In December he was confirmed as member of the re-organized 8-member Junta Nacional.<ref> it consisted of Fal Conde, Rodezno, Lamami\u00e9, Valiente, [[Juan S\u00e1enz-D\u00edez Garc\u00eda|S\u00e1enz-D\u00edez]], Mu\u00f1oz Aguilar, [[Jose Maria Arauz de Robles Estremera|Arauz de Robles]] and Zamanillo, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 241</ref> He cultivated the usual propaganda tasks,<ref>see e.g. his 1937 appearance in Palencia, ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 07.01.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2199538&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here], or in Zamora, ''Imperio'' 08.02.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000117448&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> but was entrusted also with running Secci\u00f3n Administrativa.<ref> the Carlist executive was territorially dispersed; in late 1936 and early 1937 Lamami\u00e9 and his Secci\u00f3n Administrativa were based in Burgos; Fal Conde and his collaborators were based in Toledo; Rodezno and Secci\u00f3n Pol\u00edtica resided in Salamanca, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 238</ref>\n[[File:Tropas del bando nacional (14 de 16) - Fondo Mar\u00edn-Kutxa Fototeka.jpg|thumb|requet\u00e9, 1937]]\nLamami\u00e9 was increasingly puzzled by the emerging [[Francisco Franco|Franco\u2019s]] heavy-handed rule. In early 1937 he intervened with [[Fidel D\u00e1vila Arrondo|general D\u00e1vila]] to get Fal Conde released from exile; the plea was to no avail.<ref> Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 243</ref> In February he took part in the crucial [[Insua]] meeting, where Carlist leaders and their regent discussed the threat of military-imposed political amalgamation. His stand is not clear;<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 283, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 46</ref> highly skeptical about forced unification, he did not voice decisively against it,<ref> Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, pp. 257, 263</ref> which did not spare him particular personal animadversion in the Franco headquarters.<ref> in early 1937 particular \u201canimadversaci\u00f3n\u201d in the Franco\u2019s headquarters was directed at Lamami\u00e9, Zamanillo and Araiz de Robles, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 267</ref> One contemporary historian counts him among \u201ctwo of the most persistent fence-sitters\u201d<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 287; the other one was allegedly Arauz de Robles</ref> and another locates him \u201centre un polo y el otro\u201d of the Carlist command layer. In early April he engaged in fruitless last-minute talks with [[Falange Espa\u00f1ola de las JONS|Falangist]] leaders, staged to agree a bottom-up alliance.<ref> Fidaldo, Burgue\u00f1o 1980, p. 43, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 269</ref> Eventually when faced with the [[Unification Decree (Spain, 1937)|military unification dictate]] he grudgingly opted for compliance, assuming that in case something goes wrong, \u201cour Sacred Cause would always be reborn out of its own ashes\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 291</ref>\n\n==Restless ''sansidrino''==\n[[File:Burgos 1937.jpg|thumb|left|in [[Burgos]], 1937 (2fR)]]\n[[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Don Javier]] considered Lamami\u00e9 fully loyal and authorized him to enter ruling bodies of the [[Falange Espanola Tradicionalista y de las JONS|unificated state party]],<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 293</ref> but he preferred to tone down his political engagements. Instead, he resumed activity in agricultural organisations, in particular Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico Agraria, which he still presided. Because of its acronymic name CNCA, Lamami\u00e9 and other of its top lobbyists were named \"sansidrinos\".<ref> Javier T\u00e9bar Hurtado, ''Contrarrevoluci\u00f3n y poder agrario en el franquismo. Rupturas y continuidades. La provincia de Barcelona (1939-1945)'', [PhD thesis Universidad Autonoma], Barcelona 2005, p. 115</ref> Already in June 1937 they staged a grand Asamblea Cerealista in Valladolid;<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 23.06.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000474384&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Lamami\u00e9 was confirmed in presidency of CNCA and president of one of its components, Confederaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico Agraria. Relations with the emerging Francoist regime remained correct; the traditional confederative structure was affiliated within the newly established syndicalist [[:es:Servicio Nacional del Trigo|Servicio Nacional de Trigo]] and both organizations declared total mutual understanding.<ref> ''La Espiga'' 05.11.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467802&posicion=5&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In late 1937 Lamami\u00e9 personally obtained some unspecified contracts in the Salamanca province<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 26.11.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000474517&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and in March 1938 the [[Ministry of the Interior (Spain)|Interior]] decree nominated him governor of the Burgos-based Banco de Cr\u00e9dito Local de Espa\u00f1a,<ref>some authors claim that already in 1919 Lamamie was president of \"the local [Salamanca] savings bank\", Vincent 1991, p. 165</ref> a bank entrusted with financial aid to municipalities taken over from the [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republicans]].<ref> ''Heraldo de Zamora'' 21.03.38, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2261943&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref>\n\nThroughout 1938 CNCA and the syndicalist Francoist administration were increasingly at a collision course, both advancing competitive visions of the rural regime.<ref> already during the Republican period Lamami\u00e9 voiced against fascism, which he equalled to a state dictate; he lambasted it as an imported theory not applicable to Spain, even though he saw some of its features \u2013 like \u201cemphasis upon hierarchy and combativeness\u201d \u2013 appropriate for Carlist paramilitary units, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 166</ref> The first battleground was [[Catalonia]], where on areas seized by the Nationalists the traditional local body, [[:es:Instituto Agr\u00edcola Catal\u00e1n de San Isidro|Instituto Agricola Catalan de San Isidro]], tried to reassert its domination. CNCA backed its claims and argued that they in no way interfered with officially declared vertical sindicates; a stalemate ensued.<ref> T\u00e9bar Hurtado 2005, pp. 112-113</ref> However, in October 1938 the government issued Ley de Cooperativas, which left the ''sansidrinos'' profoundly disappointed. In April 1939 CNCA demanded that clear rules of the newly established Servicio Nacional de Cooperativas get published and underlined that traditional rural organizations did not enter SNC awaiting the moment it is legally defined. Lamami\u00e9 issued declarations which in a veiled way warned against arbitrary ministerial decisions, advocated co-existence of state and private bodies, and called for recognition of 3-layer rural organizations.<ref>the 3-layer structure recommended by Lamami\u00e9 was to consist of 1) Sindicatos (to become Cooperativas), 2) Federaciones, and 3) nationaiwde Confederaci\u00f3n. His declarations of the time contained a hardly veiled criticism of Falangist syndicalism, compare ''La Espiga'' 06.05.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467867&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> During 1939 and 1940 CNCA claimed it could operate \u201csin rozar la funci\u00f3n de los Sindicatos verticales\u201d<ref> ''El Dia de Palencia'' 30.04.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2206380&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and fought marginalization.<ref>e.g. a CNCA document of October 1939 referred to earlier Francoist legislation on cooperatives, adopted on November 29, 1938, and in line with the January 28, 1906 legislation attempted to carve out a space within the rural regime where Catholic syndicated might operate, ''La Espiga'' 28.10.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467883&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here]</ref>\n[[File:Trilla 2.JPG|thumb|working the fields, early [[Francoism]]]]\nIn the early 1940s militant syndicalist Falangism enjoyed its climax in the Francoist Spain; it translated also into outcome of power struggle within the rural agricultural ambience. Despite repeated declarations of loyalty on part of CNCA and numerous assurances that in no way it posed a thread to syndical law,<ref> ''La Espiga'' 10.04.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467891&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> conservative and Christian agrarians were getting increasingly pushed into the sidelines; also Lamami\u00e9 lost steam and at one point admitted in relation to planned new regulations that \u201cno tuvo ning\u00fan reparo que objetas sino por el contario le pareci\u00f3 muy bien\u201d.<ref> T\u00e9bar Hurtado 2005, p. 186</ref> In September 1940 he left the CNCA presidency and declarations of their meeting with [[:es:Delegaci\u00f3n Nacional de Sindicatos|Delegaci\u00f3n Nacional de Sindicatos]] sounded like admitting defeat.<ref> ''El Progreso'' 06.09.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=3103081&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> With Lamami\u00e9 as honorary president<ref> ''La Espiga'' 24.12.42, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467941&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> CNCA was ultimately dissolved and incorporated into the new Uni\u00f3n Nacional de Cooperativas del Campo in 1942.<ref> Emilio Majuelo, ''Falangistas y cat\u00f3lico-sociales en liza por el control de las cooperativas'', [in:] ''Historia del presente'' 3 (2004), p. 39</ref> Lamami\u00e9 kept presiding over Banco Exterior de Cr\u00e9dito Local de Espa\u00f1a at least until the early 1940s.<ref>''Heraldo de Zamora'' 17.02.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000116871&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here]; as late as in 1943 he was involved in dealings of the Salamanca ayuntamiento, but it is not clear whether he formed part of it, ''El Adelanto'' 18.12.43, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000476403&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref>\n\n==Late Carlist activity==\n[[File:Flag of Cross of Burgundy.svg|thumbnail|left|Carlist standard]]\nAt the turn of the decades Lamami\u00e9 was barely noted officially for Carlist political activity,<ref>he was moderately engaged in Nationalist propaganda work, e.g. following takeover of Catalonia in 1939 he embarked on a tour there, ''Pensamiento Alaves'' 21.01.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000034818&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> though he did participate in Traditionalism-flavored religious services or other rallies.<ref>e.g. in August 1939 with some other Traditonalist militants \u2013 notably his fellow ex-Integrist Senante \u2013 he took part in religious service to employees of Editorial Tradicionalista who perished ruring the war, ''Lab\u00f3r'' 28.08.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=3028361&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> He used to take part in confidential meetings; in 1940 when returning from such a session with a [[Carlo-francoism|carlo-francoist]] general [[:es:Ricardo Rada|Ricardo Rada]] he suffered a car accident<ref> Manuel de Santa Cruz [Alberto Ruiz de Galarreta], ''Apuntes y documentos para la historia del tradicionalismo espa\u00f1ol: 1939-1966'', vols. 1-3, Seville 1979, p. 95</ref> and barely managed to dispose of related potentially damaging documentation before the [[Guardia Civil]] patrol arrived.<ref> ''Heraldo de Zamora'' 26.01.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000116852&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> The same year he corresponded with [[:es:Direcci\u00f3n General de Seguridad|Director General de Seguridad]] protesting repressions against Carlist militants;<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, p. 95</ref> on another front, he conferred about keeping the [[Alfonsism|Alfonsists]] in check.<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, p. 26</ref> In 1941 Lamami\u00e9 supplied Don Javier with his political analysis, but its content is not known.<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, p. 82</ref> During the climax of the [[Nazi]] might in Europe he advocated a neutral Spanish policy<ref> in a 1941 letter to Serrano Su\u00f1er Lamami\u00e9 quoted the case of Carlos VII, who assumed a neutral stand during the international 1898 crisis, and this of Jaime III, who advocated neutrality during the First World War </ref> and declared that individual Carlists were free to enlist to [[Divisi\u00f3n Azul]], but Comun\u00edon would in no way endorse the recruitment.<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, pp. 137-140</ref> In another letter, sent 1942, he protested to [[Ramon Serrano Suner|Ramon Serrano Serrano]] against official measures applied to Fal Conde.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 92</ref> In 1943 he co-signed a large document addressed to Franco and known as ''Reclamaci\u00f3n de Poder''; its Carlist signatories called to do away with syndicalist features and to introduce a traditionalist monarchy.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 96, Alcal\u00e1 2001, p. 52</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1940s Lamami\u00e9 was among moderate anti-Francoists; during a 1944 monarchist gathering which included also the Alfonsists he voted against mounting a coup, intended to topple the caudillo.<ref> Alcal\u00e1 2001, p. 57</ref> In 1947 he took part in the first meeting of Carlist executive since the 1937 Insua session and entered the re-established 5-member Consejo Nacional.<ref> the Council consisted of Fal Conde, Valiente, Zamanillo, Saenz-Diez and Lamami\u00e9, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 106, Canal 2000, p. 350</ref> In support of the moderately anti-Francoist falcondista strategy he opposed the vehemently anti-Francoist [[Maurici de Sivatte i de Bobadilla|sivattista]] line, increasingly visible in the late 1940s.<ref> Alcal\u00e1 2001, pp. 72, 78</ref> In the early 1950s as secretary of the Carlist executive he prepared documentation supposed to back the royal claim of Don Javier, who until then had posed as a regent and did not advance explicit monarchical claims;<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 132</ref> he edited the final version of the declaration, made by the claimant during the Eucharistic Congress in [[Barcelona]] in 1952.<ref> Jacek Bartyzel, ''Nic bez Boga, nic wbrew tradycji'', Radzymin 2015, {{ISBN|9788360748732}}, p. 251</ref> At that time he was already suffering from bad health and in the early 1950s he used a wheelchair;<ref> ''Nueva Alcarr\u00eda'' 24.07.54, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5083114&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> however, in 1954 he accepted membership in the renewed party Junta Nacional and its acting governing body Comisi\u00f3n Permanente.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 138</ref> In the mid-1950s the Carlist stand versus the regime changed from opposition to cautious co-operation; it was sealed by dismissal of Fal Conde and by Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Valiente assuming political leadership. The latter still considered Lamami\u00e9 a loyal \u201chombre firme y en\u00e9rgico\u201d<ref> Mercedes V\u00e1zquez de Prada, ''El final de una ilusi\u00f3n. Auge y declive del tradicionalismo carlista (1957-1967)'', Madrid 2016, {{ISBN|9788416558407}}, pp. 40-41</ref> and sounded him upon assuming secretariat of the ruling party junta. In 1956 Lamami\u00e9 replied that though sick, he was ready to offer his name as \u201cuna garant\u00eda absoluta de defensa de la Causa\u201d;<ref> Mercedes V\u00e1zquez de Prada, ''El nuevo rumbo pol\u00edtico del carlismo hacia la colaboraci\u00f3n con el r\u00e9gimen (1955-56)'', [in:] ''Hispania'' 69 (2009), pp. 190-191</ref> his death came earlier.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Integrism (Spain)]]\n* [[Carlism]]\n* [[Traditionalism (Spain)]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Martin Blinkhorn, ''Carlism and Crisis in Spain 1931-1939'', Cambridge 2008, {{ISBN|9780521086349}}\n* Hermanos Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Alonso, ''Recuerdos de la guerra: Espa\u00f1a 1936-1939: vividos y relatados por los autores'', M\u00e9xico 1991, {{ISBN|9789688590317}}\n* Jes\u00fas Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez, ''Actitudes pol\u00edtico religiosas de la minor\u00eda agraria de las Cortes Constituyentes de 1931'' [PhD Universidad Complutense 1974], Madrid 2015\n* Emilio Majuelo Gil, ''Falangistas y cat\u00f3licos sociales en liza por el control de las cooperativas'', [in:] ''Historia del presente'' 3 (2004), pp. 29-43\n* Antonio M. Moral Roncal, ''La cuesti\u00f3n religiosa en la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola: Iglesia y carlismo'', Madrid 2009, {{ISBN|9788497429054}}\n* Juan Carlos Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo de Quir\u00f3s, ''El Carlismo, la Rep\u00fablica y la Guerra Civil (1936-1937). De la conspiraci\u00f3n a la unificaci\u00f3n'', Madrid 1996, {{ISBN|8487863523}}\n* [[Antonio P\u00e9rez de Olaguer]], ''Piedras Vivas. Biografia del Capellan Requete Jose M. Lamamie de Clairac y Alonso'', Madrid 1939\n* Mary Vincent, ''Catholicism in the Second Spanish Republic: Religion and Politics in Salamanca, 1930-1936'', London 1996, {{ISBN|9780198206132}}\n[[File:Family of Lamamie de Clairac.jpg|thumb|with family, 1920s]]\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.geni.com/people/Jose-Maria-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019299952895 Lamamie at ''Geni'' genealogical site]\n* [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXLDA.fmt&DOCS=1-125&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. Lamamie at the official Cortes service]\n* {{YouTube|Es5PCrb2cTQ|''Para maior gl\u00f3ria de Deus'' - Brazilian homage to Lamamie's son}}\n* {{YouTube|uhK1ER3B4Hg|''Por Dios y por Espa\u00f1a''; contemporary Carlist propaganda}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Colina, Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda}}\n[[Category:Castilian-Leonese politicians]]\n[[Category:Carlists]]\n[[Category:Far-right politicians in Spain]]\n[[Category:People of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Salamanca]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic activists]]\n[[Category:Spanish anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Spanish landowners]]\n[[Category:Spanish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Spanish monarchists]]\n[[Category:National syndicalists]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of the Spanish Civil War (National faction)]]\n[[Category:Spanish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Colina\n| image                     = \n{{CSS image crop\n|Image = Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac.png\n|bSize = 230\n|cWidth = 220\n|cHeight = 300\n|oTop = 00\n|oLeft = 10\n|Location=center\n}}\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_date                = 1887\n| birth_place               = [[Salamanca]], Spain\n| death_date                = 1956\n| death_place               = Salamanca, Spain\n| body_discovered           = \n| death_cause               = \n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = [[Spanish people|Spanish]]\n| citizenship               = \n| other_names               = \n| known_for                 = politician\n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| employer                  = \n| notable works             = \n| occupation                = landowner\n| years_active              = \n| home_town                 = \n| salary                    = \n| networth                  = \n| height                    = \n| weight                    = \n| title                     = \n| term                      =\n| predecessor               = \n| successor                 =\n| party                     = [[Integrism (Spain)|Integrism]], [[Carlism]]\n| opponents                 = \n| boards                    = \n| spouse                    = \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| relations                 = \n| callsign                  = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| website                   = \n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n| misc                      =\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Colina''' (1887-1956) was a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] politician. He supported the [[Traditionalism (Spain)|Traditionalist]] cause, until the early 1930s as an [[Integrism (Spain)|Integrist]] and afterwards as a [[Carlist]]. Among the former he headed the regional [[Le\u00f3n (historical region)|Le\u00f3n]] branch, among the latter he rose to nationwide executive and became one of the party leaders in the late 1930s and the 1940s. In 1931-1936 he served 2 terms in the [[Cortes Generales|Cortes]]; in 1915-1920 he was member of the [[Salamanca]] [[ayuntamiento]]. In historiography he is known mostly as representative of [[Castile (historical region)|Castilian]] ''[[Landowner|terratenientes]]''; as president of [[:es:Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria|Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria]] he tried to preserve the landowner-dominated rural regime, first opposing the [[Second Spanish Republic|Republican]] and later the [[Francoism|Francoist]] designs.\n\n==Family and youth==\n[[File:Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac.png|thumb|160px|left|[[:es:Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac|father]]]]\nThe Lamami\u00e9s originated from the [[France|French]] [[Languedoc]];<ref> ''La elegida como esposa: Eulalia Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Nicola\u00fa'', [in:] ''RamonSalasLarrazabal'' service 12.09.14, available at a WP-blocked ''WordPress'' service, 12.09.14; other sources claim the family came from Toulose, ''Etienne de La Mamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Etienne-de-La-Mamye-de-Clairac/6000000019312881943 here]</ref> Etienne La Mamye de Clairac<ref> born 1646, died 1717, ''Etienne de La Mamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Etienne-de-La-Mamye-de-Clairac/6000000019312881943 here]</ref> was a military and held high administrative posts in [[County of Flanders|Flanders]] in the late 17th century.<ref> he is referred as \u201cmariscal de campo\u201d and \u201cgobernador de Sant Omer (Flandes)\u201d, ''Claudio Diego Jacobo Lamamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Familia Lamamie de Clairac'' blogspot 16.01.10, available [http://lamamiedeclairac.blogspot.com/ here]</ref> His son arrived in Spain with [[Philip V of Spain|Felipe de Anjou]] in the 1720s and became known as Claudio Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Dubois;<ref> born 1703, died 1771; reportedly born in Toul near Meurthe-et-Moselle (Lorraine) he died in Huelva, ''Claudio Diego Jacobo Lamamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Claudio-Diego-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Dubois/6000000019301505267 here]</ref> he served on various military command posts during the following 4 decades.<ref> ''Claudio Diego Jacobo Lamamye de Clairac'' entry, [in:] ''Familia Lamamie de Clairac'' blogspot 16.01.10, available [http://lamamiedeclairac.blogspot.com/ here]</ref> Claudio\u2019 son Miguel Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Villalonga<ref> born 1748, death date unknown, ''Miguel Lamamie de Clairac y Villalonga'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Miguel-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Vilallonga/6000000019301587446 here]</ref> was the first to settle on estates granted to him near [[Salamanca Province|Salamanca]] in the late 18th century.<ref>''Ramas Espa\u00f1olas II. Lamamie de Clairac \u2013 resumindo'', [in:] ''Familia Lamamie de Clairac'' blogspot 06.01.10, available [http://lamamiedeclairac.blogspot.com/2010/01/ramas-espanolas-ii-lamamie-de-clairac.html here]</ref> His son an the grandfather of Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda, Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Tirado (1784-1847),<ref> born 1784, died 1847, ''Jose Ramon Lamamie de Clairac y Tirado'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Jose-Ramon-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Tirado/6000000019301567238 here]</ref> a military like his ancestors, fought against the French during [[Napoleonic wars]]; though he massively benefitted from [[Liberalism in Spain|liberal]] ''[[Spanish confiscation|desamortizaci\u00f3n]]'',<ref> Antonio Luis L\u00f3pez Mart\u00ednez, ''Ganader\u00edas de lidia y ganaderos: historia y econom\u00eda de los toros de lidia en Espa\u00f1a'', Sevilla 2002, {{ISBN|9788447207428}}, p. 152</ref> he turned a Carlist supporter when senile.<ref>''El Siglo Futuro'' 27.10.19, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000366219&page=2 here]; some authors note him as ancestors as \u201callegedly \u201cof French legitimist antecedents\u201d, Martin Blinkhorn, ''Carlism and Crisis in Spain 1931-1939'', Cambridge 2008, {{ISBN|9780521086349}}, p. 53. It is not clear what legitimism is mentioned, as the French ancestors arrived in Spain before the legitimist issue arose in France, while the the Spanish ancestors engaged in legitimist cause were not French</ref> His son and the father of Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda, [[:es:Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac|Juan Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Trespalacios]] (1831-1919),<ref> ''Juan Lamamie de Clairac y Trespalacios'', [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Juan-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-Trespalacios/6000000019300611606 here]</ref> was among the largest provincial landowners.<ref>\u201centre los principales terratenientes y ganaderos de la provincia\u201d, Manuel Mar\u00eda Urrutia Le\u00f3n, Manuel Mar\u00eda Urrutia, ''Miguel de Unamuno desconocido'', Salamanca 2007, {{ISBN|9788478003846}}, p. 70</ref> Detained for plotting a legitimist rising,<ref> he studied law in [[University of Salamanca|Salamanca]]; in the late 1860s he served as the Carlist subcomisario regio for Salamanca province and as provincial deputy in the 1870s; arrested in 1872, he was released on word of honor and got self-exiled to France. He returned in 1874, but in line with his pledge, did not engage in further conspiracy, ''El Siglo Futuro'' 27.10.19, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000366219&page=2 here]</ref> he returned from exile in the 1870s; he then owned numerous Carlist provincial periodicals.<ref> Lamami\u00e9 founded and managed ''La Tesis'', ''La Tradici\u00f3n, La Regi\u00f3n, La Informaci\u00f3n'' and ''El Salmantino''; the first two he managed with Enrique Gil Robles and Manuel Sanchez Asensio </ref> In the 1880s Lamami\u00e9 joined the breakaway Integrist branch of Traditionalism and was its regional Le\u00f3n jef\u00e9; in 1907-1910 he served as Integrist [[Member of parliament|MP]]<ref> as a wealthy terrateniente Lamamie was in position to buy votes of his \u201ccolonos\u201d, Ros Ana Guti\u00e9rrez Lloret, ''Las elecciones de 1907 en Salamanca: un ejemplo de la movilizaci\u00f3n y confrontaci\u00f3n electoral cat\u00f3lica en la Espa\u00f1a de la Restauraci\u00f3n'', [in:] ''Studia Historica. Historia Contemporanea'' 22 (2004), p. 333</ref> in the Cortes<ref> see the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=1-1&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858870%29.NDIP. here]</ref> and entered the national party executive.<ref> along [[Juan Olaz\u00e1bal Ramery|Juan Ol\u00e1zabal]], Javier Sanz Larumbe, Marqu\u00e9s de Casa Ulloa and Juan Balanz\u00f3 y Pons, Mar\u00eda Jes\u00fas Izquierdo, ''El Sexisme a la universitat: estudi comparatiu del personal assalariat de les universitats p\u00fabliques catalanes'', Barcelona 1999, {{ISBN|9788449015731}}, p. 98</ref>\n\nFollowing childless death of his wife, in 1882 Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Trespalacios re-married<ref> ''El Siglo Futuro'' 31.10.19, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000366326&page=2 here]</ref> with Celestina de la Colina Fern\u00e1ndez-Cavada (1859-1946), the native of [[Burgos]].<ref> she was daughter to Luis Esteban de la Colina y Gonz\u00e1lez de la Riva and Felipa Fern\u00e1ndez-Cavada y Espadero </ref> The couple had at least 8 children, born when the father was in his 50s and 60s;<ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairas was short and of very meager posture; it is not clear whether it was anyhow related to advanced age of his father upon conception </ref> 4 of them died in early infancy.<ref> born between 1885 and 1894, Jacinto, Mar\u00eda del Carmen, Mar\u00eda de la Paz and Mar\u00eda de las Dolores died before reaching the teen age, ''Jacinto Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Jacinto-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000025818146636 here], ''Maria del Carmen Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-Luisa-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019359657621 here], ''Mar\u00eda de las Dolores Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-de-los-Dolores-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000025818146632 here]</ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda was born as the third son, but as his oldest brother perished and the second oldest became a religious,<ref> Juan (1886-1963) served as a chaplain Cantabria, ''Juan Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Juan-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019359657617 here]</ref> it was him who inherited the family wealth.<ref> other surviving siblings identified were Mar\u00eda Luisa (1883-1951), ''Mar\u00eda Luisa Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-Luisa-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019359657621 here], and Mar\u00eda de la Pur\u00edsima (1892-1954), ''Mar\u00eda de la Purisima Lamamie de Clairac y de la Colina'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available - [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-de-la-Pur%C3%ADsima-Lamami\u00e9-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/600000001935965762 here]5</ref> Some sources suggest he received early education in the Salamanca Instituto General y T\u00e9cnico,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 20.06.05, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7503899&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> others maintain that he frequented Seminario de Salamanca, then studied with \u201clos jesu\u00edtas en Comillas\u201d, and obtained bachillerato in the [[Jesuit Order|Jesuit]] [[Valladolid]] college<ref> Jes\u00fas Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez, ''Actitudes pol\u00edtico religiosas de la minor\u00eda agraria de las Cortes Constituyentes de 1931'' [PhD Universidad Complutense 1974], Madrid 2015, p. 179</ref> in or around 1905.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He then studied law in [[University of Valladolid|Valladolid]]<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 179</ref> and graduated with excellent marks in 1909;<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 09.10.09, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039895&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> some sources mention also his agricultural education.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> \n[[File:Sofia Alonso Moreno with her Lamamie de Clairac Alonso sons.jpg|thumb|wife and sons]]\nIn 1910<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 02.04.10, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5038677&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Lamami\u00e9 married a local girl, Sof\u00eda Alonso Moreno (1887-1970);<ref> ''Sof\u00eda Alonso Moreno'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Sof%C3%ADa-Alonso/6000000019299983937 here]</ref> she came from the local bourgeoisie family.<ref> her father, Tom\u00e1s Alonso del Moral, was the native of Valladolid. ''Tomas Alonso del Moral'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Tom%C3%A1s-Alonso-del-Moral/6000000019312856267 here]. He was known as \u201cconocido comerciante\u201d and member of the local ayuntamiento and other bodies, ''El Fomento de Salamanca'' 31.01.98, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5021849&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]. For her mother Aurea Moreno Brusi (1849-1937), the native of Salamanca, see ''Aurea Moreno Brusi'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Aurea-Moreno-Brusi/6000000019312856262 here]</ref> They settled at Lamami\u00e9 family estate in the Salamanca province, in-between [[Alba de Tormes]]<ref> it seems that among many estates owned, the Lamamies resided on the one named \u201cMartill\u00e1n\u201d, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 59</ref> and [[Babilafuente]].<ref> another location mentioned is San Crist\u00f3bal de Fuente, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 59; it has not been identified. Another scholar claims that the Lamamie estates were located slightly elsewhere, namely in the Martillan county, Mary Vincent, ''Catholicism in the Second Republic: Religion and Politics in Salamanca, 1930-1936'' [PhD thesis University of Oxford], Oxford 1991, p. 119</ref> Though Lamami\u00e9 is often referred in historiography as \u201crico ganadero y terrateniente\u201d<ref>Jos\u00e9 Andr\u00e9s Gallego, Ant\u00f3n M. Pazos, ''Archivo Gom\u00e1: documentos de la Guerra Civil'', vol. 9, Madrid 2001, {{ISBN|9788400084295}}, p. 411. Another scholar claims that in case of Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 the references to cattle-breeding are erroneous, see Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 179. Indeed, in the 1940s and 1950s fairly frequent press notes to toros de lidia coming from the Lamamie ganaderia referred to Leopoldo Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac, ''Imperio'' 15.08.54, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000121554&posicion=5&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> or \u201cgrande terrateniente\u201d<ref> \u00c1ngel Bahamonde, ''14 de abril. La Rep\u00fablica'', Madrid 2011, {{ISBN|9788401347764}}, p. 312</ref> it is not clear what the actual size of his estates was. Various sources claim that the couple had 9<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 179</ref> to 11<ref> ''Fallecimento Pe. Luis Lamamie de Clairac'', [in:] ''Pjicohna'' blogspot 18.02.10, available [http://pjiconha.blogspot.com/2010/03/falecimento-peluis-lamamie-de-clairac.html here]</ref> children. Raised in the very religious ambience,<ref>female children were educated by the Handmaids of the Sacred Heart, their five brothers went to the Jesuits in Madrid, Vincent 1991, p. 53; they were raised according to a very traditional model and address their father with the formal \"usted\", Vincent 1991, p. 268</ref> at least 6 of them joined religious orders;<ref> at least two daughters became nuns, Mar\u00eda Luisa and Mar\u00eda del Pilar, see Ma. Teresa Camarero-Nu\u00f1ez, ''Mi nombre nuevo, Magnificat'', Madrid 1961 </ref> some served in America,<ref> a Jesuit friar Luis died in Brazil, ''Fallecimento Pe. Luis Lamamie de Clairac'', [in:] ''Pjicohna'' blogspot 18.02.10, available [http://pjiconha.blogspot.com/2010/03/falecimento-peluis-lamamie-de-clairac.html here]; see also a YT homage to Luis, available [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Es5PCrb2cTQ here]. Also a Jesuit friar Ignacio died in Mexico, ''Agradecimiento a Dios y a vosotros'', [in:] ''Vallisoletana Dosmil'' 3 (2004), p. 3 </ref> some grew to local prominence<ref> Juan (another Jesuit) was headmaster of the Salamanca seminary, ''Juan Lamamie de Clairac Alonso SJ'', [in:] ''La Nueva Espa\u00f1a'' 28.04.16, available [https://www.lne.es/tags/juan-lamamie-de-clairac-alonso-sj.html here]</ref> and one son was killed as a [[requet\u00e9]] chaplain in 1937.<ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamamie de Clairac (1911-1937) perished during fightings in Sierra de Guadarrama in February 1937, Hermanos Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Alonso, ''Recuerdos de la guerra: Espa\u00f1a 1936-1939: vividos y relatados por los autores'', M\u00e9xico 1991, {{ISBN|9789688590317}}, p. 155, see also Ram\u00f3n Grande del Brio, ''Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamamie de Clairac y Alonso entry'', [in:] ''Real Academia de Historia'' service, available [http://dbe.rah.es/biografias/27230/jose-maria-lamamie-de-clairac-y-alonso here]</ref> The family heir Tom\u00e1s Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Alonso did not become a public figure, though he held high executive functions in [[SEAT]] and other companies.<ref> Ruth Whiteside (ed.), ''Major Financial Institutions of Europe 1994'', London 1994, {{ISBN|9789401114608}}, p. 196</ref> Neither the Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Delgado nor the Lia\u00f1o Pacheco Lamami\u00e9<ref> ''Maria del Carmen Lamamie de Clairac Alonso'' entry, [in:] ''Geni'' genealogical service, available [https://www.geni.com/people/Maria-del-Carmen-Lamamie-de-Clairac-Alonso/6000000019299764726 here]. For details on the Lia\u00f1o Pacheco y Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac offspring see Jaime de Salazar y Acha, ''Estudio hist\u00f3rico sobre una familia extreme\u00f1a, los S\u00e1nchez Arjona'', Madrid 2000, {{ISBN|9788488833013}}, p. 531</ref> grandchildren grew to prominence; the best known, Pilar Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac Delgado, is a [[pediatrician]].<ref> ''Dra Pilar Lamamie de Clairac Delgado'', [in:] ''RuberInternacional'' service, available [https://www.ruberinternacional.es/es/cuadro-medico/equipos/equipo-dr-jose-casas-rivero/dra-pilar-lamamie-clairac-delgado here]</ref>\n\n==Early public activity==\n{{CSS image crop\n|Image = \u00c1ngel Herrera Oria.png\n|bSize = 200\n|cWidth = 160\n|cHeight = 240\n|oTop = 30\n|oLeft = 10\n|Location = left\n|Description = [[Angel Herrera Oria|Herrera Oria]]\n}}\nIn 1904-1906 as a teenager Lamami\u00e9 signed various open letters, usually protesting alleged official anti-Catholic measures<ref> ''El Labaro'' 04.06.06. available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5034813&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> or publicly professing Christian faith.<ref>''El Siglo Futuro'' 28.07.04, available [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000247041&page=1 here]; in 1905 Lamami\u00e9 asked God to allow him to become \u201ca genuinely Christian young man\u201d, ''La Basilica Teresiana'' 15.09.05, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5016931&posicion=29&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> He earned his name in history books already in 1908, when within a group of equally young 9 signatories \u2013 including [[\u00c1ngel Herrera Oria]]<ref> Jos\u00e9 Luis Orella Mart\u00ednez, ''El origen del primer catolicismo social espa\u00f1ol'', [PhD thesis] Madrid 2012, p. 42</ref> - he co-founded Asociaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica Nacional de J\u00f3venes Propagandistas,<ref>the other 7 co-founders were Luis de Aristiz\u00e1bal, Jaime Chicharro, Jos\u00e9 Fern\u00e1ndez de Henestrosa, Manuel G\u00f3mez Rold\u00e1n, Angel Herrera Oria, Jos\u00e9 de Polanco and Gerardo Requejo, Luis S\u00e1nchez Movell\u00e1n de la Riva, ''Cien a\u00f1os de la Asociaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica'', [in:] ''El Diario Monta\u00f1es'' 10.12.09, available [https://www.eldiariomontanes.es/20091210/opinion/articulos/cien-anos-asociacion-catolica-20091210.html here]</ref> later known as [[:es:Asociaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica de Propagandistas|ACNDP]].<ref> V\u00edctor Manuel Arbeloa Muru, ''La Iglesia que busc\u00f3 la concordia'', Madrid 2011, {{ISBN|9788499206363}}, p. 66</ref> Indeed in 1909-1914 he engaged in Catholic propaganda, noted e.g. when speaking at local Catholic rallies,<ref>''El Salmantino'' 03.04.09, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039857&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here], or ''El Salmantino'' 23.04.10, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5038680&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> entering committees which co-ordinated religious projects,<ref>e.g. in 1910 he entered the local junta organizadora of the project to declare social sovereignity of Christ in Spain, ''El Salmantino'' 15.11.10, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5040565&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]. The Lamamie estate hosted the first monument in Spain dedicated to Christ the King. By the 1930s it became the focus of annual processions, presided over by Jose Maria, Vincent 1991, p. 119</ref> greeting bishops,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 06.12.13, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506225&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> featuring prominently at local feasts<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 23.02.14, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507357&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> or contributing to ''El Salmantino'' daily.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 09.10.09, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039895&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Some of these engagements were increasingly flavored with \u201cpropaganda cat\u00f3lico-social\u201d.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 17.05.12, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5036628&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Some time in the 1910s Lamami\u00e9 left ACNDP, accusing them of \"betraying the Catholic cause\".<ref>the Lamamie family has even warned Jose Maria Gil Robles against joining ACNDP, Vincent 1991, p. 153</ref> \n\nIn the early 1910s Lamami\u00e9 opened his own law desk in [[Madrid]], though little is known of its activity;<ref>in 1913 Lamami\u00e9 opened the law office in Madrid which was supposed to deal with \u201ctoda clase de asuntos de Derecho, especialmente civiles, y a testamentarias\u201d, ''La Victoria'' 13.12.13, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5024204&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> he remained active in the Salamanca family [[wheat]] business.<ref>e.g. in 1912 Lamami\u00e9 enlarged family holdings by new purchases, ''El Salmantino'' 04.12.12, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039035&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> At that time he was already vice-president of the local branch of the Integrist organisation.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 12.01.11, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5036184&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the mid-1910s approaching the right-wing [[Antonio Maura|Maurista]] faction of the [[Conservative Party (Spain)|Conservatives]],<ref>e.g. during the 1915 elections Lamami\u00e9 supported a Maurista candidate, ''Libertad'' 22.03.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5022022&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> in 1915 he decided to run on the Integrist ticket<ref>''El Adelanto'' 19.11.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506135&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]; at times he was reported as a maurista, ''El Adelanto'' 18.10.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506105&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> to the [[town hall]] and was elected with no opposing candidate standing.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 15.11.15, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506129&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the ayuntamiento he was counted among representatives of the extreme right and one of the most intelligent [[Councillor|concejales]] at the same time.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 11.08.16, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7500494&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> As the only Integrist councilor he tended to alliance with Maurista, but also [[Jaime, Duke of Madrid|Jaimista]] members.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 04.05.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5039936&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Press notes present him as an active and belligerent politician, concerned primarily with economic issues; given heavy debt burden of the city and financial problems ensuing,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 21.04.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507037&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> in 1917 he supported governmental nomination of a new [[alcalde]].<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 16.03.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507453&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the late 1910s Lamami\u00e9 already presided over work of some municipal committees.<ref>e.g. in 1917 Lamamie presiding over electoral works to renew composition of the ayuntamiento in partial elections, ''El Salmantino'' 22.12.17, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037996&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> He was initially supposed to run for re-election; however, for reasons which remain unclear and were probably related to failed coalition talks<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 07.02.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506740&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> he withdrew from the race and ceased as concejal in 1920.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 09.01.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506715&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref>\n[[File:Juan Olazabal.JPG|thumb|160px|[[Integrism (Spain)|Integrist]] leader [[Juan Olaz\u00e1bal Ramery|Olazabal]]]]\nAlready in the late 1910s and thanks to his connections to Integrist parliamentarians like [[Manuel Senante Martinez|Manual Senante]], Lamami\u00e9\u2019s proposals ended up at ministerial desks.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.06.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5038497&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In [[Spanish general election, 1918|1918]] he tried to enter nationwide politics himself; following in the footsteps of his father, he decided to run for the Cortes as an Integrist candidate from the district of Salamanca. In all boroughs he trashed the left-wing candidate [[Miguel de Unamuno]], but by a slight margin he was himself defeated by a Liberal [[Conde de Romanones|Romanonista]] candidate;<ref>Lamami\u00e9 gathered 4,900 votes, while his opponent collected 5,200 votes, ''El Adelanto'' 26.02.8, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506452&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here], see also ''El Adelanto'' 25.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506451&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> this did not prevent his supporters from claiming \u201ctriunfo moral\u201d.<ref>''El Salmantino'' 08.03.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037836&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here], also ''El Salmantino'' 11.03.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037838&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> In the early [[Spanish general election, 1919|elections called for 1919]] Lamami\u00e9 tried his hand again. Though he was known as councilor, local landowner, son to former deputy, Integrist, zealous Catholic propagandist and activist of local agrarian syndicates<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 18.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> he lost again; this time he was decisively defeated by a former military who ran as an independent Conservative candidate.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 02.06.19, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507751&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He was not noted as renewing his efforts in last elections of the [[Restoration (Spain)|Restoration]] era in the early 1920s;<ref>one scholar claims that \"Lamamie de Clairac had himself been sufficiently involved with the 'old' politics to be returned to the Cortes as a deputy for the city of Salamanca just before Primo's coup in May 1923\", Vincent 1991, p. 180; it is not clear what is meant here</ref> he welcomed the 1923 Primo coup enthusiastically.<ref>Vincent 1991, p. 181; the author quotes Lamamie's interview to ''El Debate'' of October 1923</ref>\n\n==In agricultural organisations==\n[[File:Jose Maria Lamamie de Clairac around the year of 1930s.jpg|left|thumb|160px|Lamamie, 1920s]]\nAlready in 1918 Lamami\u00e9 was vice-president of local Salmantine federation of agrarian syndicates.<ref> ''El Salmantino'' 19.02.18, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5037821&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> After death of his father the following year he inherited most of the family estates and became \u201cone of the largest landowners in the Salamanca district\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 57; also \u201cwealthy, locally powerful stockbreeder and landlord\u201d - Blinkhorn 2008, p. 53. The information about stockbreeding is incorrect </ref> Since the early 1920s he engaged heavily in works of local agricultural organisations; formally they posed as representing all rural stakeholders, but were usually dominated by landholders and adhered to the Catholic social doctrine. The key one was Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lica Agr\u00edcola,<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 01.03.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7506759&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> renamed later to Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria Salmantina; rising to its president, since 1921 Lamami\u00e9 represented the organization in the provincial C\u00e1mara Agricola.<ref>''El Adelanto'' 28.11.21, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7508182&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here], for 1923 see ''El Adelanto'' 17.04.23, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000350025&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> In 1923 he rose beyond the province as he became one of the leaders of confederation of agrarian syndicates in the region of Le\u00f3n;<ref> ''La Correspondencia de Espa\u00f1a'' 18.10.23, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7146847&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> in 1925 it evolved into Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria de las Federaciones Castellano Leonesas.<ref>''Bolet\u00edn de Acci\u00f3n Social \u00f3rgano de la Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria Salmantina y de las instituciones promovidas por la Junta Diocesana de Acci\u00f3n Catolica-Social'' 4 (1925), available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000167060&posicion=11&presentacion=pagina here] </ref>\n\nAs representative of agrarian organizations he lobbied at various official administrative and self-governmental bodies, like Consejo Provincial de Fomento<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 01.10.20, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=7507854&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and regional institutions;<ref> ''La Victoria'' 19.07.24, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5026806&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> already a recognized personality, at official feasts at times he spoke right after the civil governor.<ref> ''La Victoria'' 10.10.25, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5026880&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In 1925 latest he was nominated ''comisario regio de fomento'', a provincial delegate of [[Ministry of Development (Spain)|Ministry of Infrastructure]];<ref>''El Adelanto'' 16.12.25, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000350844&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]; Lamamie served as comisario regio de fomento and head of Consejo Provincial de Fomento at least until 1928, ''El Adelanto'' 24.01.28, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351495&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> the same year he grew to president of Federaci\u00f3n de Sindicatos Cat\u00f3licos.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 16.12.25, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000350844&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In 1927 Lamami\u00e9 was in executive of Uni\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico Agraria Castellano Leonesa; he tried to endorse its vision of rural regime<ref>it included regulation of rental contracts and advanced a theory named \u201csocialismo agrario\u201d, ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 09.02.27, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201441&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> and took part in Congreso Nacional Cerealista;<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 06.09.27, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351376&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here], also Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 60</ref> also during following years he used to give lectures on organisation of agricultural labor.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 19.10.29, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000352035&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In the late 1920s he focused on presidency of Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico Agraria Salmantina and activity in Acci\u00f3n Social Cat\u00f3lico Agraria.<ref> ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 26.05.28, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2206547&posicion=5&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He formed part of Comis\u00edon Trigueroharinaria within Comisi\u00f3n Arbitral Agr\u00edcola, a [[Miguel Primo de Rivera|primoderiverista]] arbitration committee supervised by Ministry of Agriculture,<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 180</ref> and was member of C\u00e1mara de la Propiedad R\u00fastica.<ref>''Bolet\u00edn de Acci\u00f3n Social \u00f3rgano de la Federaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria Salmantina y de las instituciones promovidas por la Junta Diocesana de Acci\u00f3n Catolica-Social'' 11 (1929), available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000167186&posicion=22&presentacion=pagina here]. One scholar claims that \"Proprietors of Rural Estates\" organization - not sure whether same as C\u00e1mara de la Propiedad R\u00fastica - was founded \"in response to the Republic's plans for agrarian reform\", Vincent 1991, p. 167 </ref> He grew to vice-president of Confederaci\u00f3n Hidrogr\u00e1fica del Duero,<ref>''Diario de Burgos'' 31.01.29, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000443371&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]; the company was active at least since 1926, ''El Adelanto'' 19.12.26, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351156&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> but scaled down his activity as a lawyer.<ref> in 1928 Lamamie ceased as member of Junta de Gobierno of the Salamanca colegio de abogados, ''El Adelanto'' 25.05.28, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000351598&posicion=6&presentacion=pagina here]</ref>\n[[File:Castroj3.JPG|thumb|wheat fields, [[Castile (historical region)|Castile]]]]\nFollowing the fall of [[Miguel Primo de Rivera|Primo]] Lamami\u00e9 assumed more militant political stand; in 1930 he agonized about \u201cgrave situation in agriculture\u201d<ref> ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 02.05.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201729&posicion=12&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and demanded permanent consultative representation of landowners\u2019 federations in Madrid;<ref> ''El Dia de Palencia'' 14.04.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201716&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> indeed he was shortly nominated member of Consejo del Economia Nacional.<ref> ''Las Provincias'' 16.12.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000320247&posicion=6&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> On first pages he claimed that rural syndicates did not intend to engage in politics,<ref>Vincent 1991, p. 183</ref> but on the other hand when representing \u201clabrador castellano\u201d they looked beyond purely agricultural interest.<ref>''El Dia de Palencia'' 13.05.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201738&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here]; for another huge front-page interview see ''El Dia de Palencia'' 30.05.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2201752&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> In June he co-founded Acci\u00f3n Castellana,<ref>its flag was that of the fatherland and \"Religion, Family, Order, Property and Monarchy\" slogan, Vincent 1991, p. 179</ref> supposed to promote \u201caspiraciones nacionales y agrarias\u201d,<ref> ''Mir\u00f3briga'' 29.06.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000166113&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> though he also appeared on meetings of Partido Provincial Agrario.<ref> ''El Dia de Palencia'' 10.10.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2205178&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> He called to do away with ruling corrupted oligarchies,<ref>one scholar claims Lamamie was part of the primoderiverista oligarchy himself as Salamanca's representative \"in the dictator's National Assembly\", Vincent 1991, p. 181. There is no confirmation of his place in Asamblea Nacional Consultiva, and the official Cortes service does not list him (or any other Lamamie) as such</ref> but opposed the rising republican tide by lambasting \u201cfalse liberties and democratic absurdities\u201d;<ref>in March 1931 Lamami\u00e9 demanded also derogation of penal code adopted during the dictatorship, ''El Adelanto'' 05.03.31, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000352460&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> according to his vision, [[Castile (historical region)|Castile]] as the heart of Spain remembered that \u201cen primer t\u00e9rmino Dios\u201d.<ref> Jaume Claret Miranda, ''Esta salvaje pesadilla: Salamanca en la Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola'', Salamanca 2007, {{ISBN|9788484329015}}, p. 9</ref> In September he declared running to the future Cortes in name of Sindicatos Cat\u00f3licos Agrarios,<ref> ''Heraldo Alaves'' 06.09.30, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000030524&posicion=6&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> but in February 1931 specified he would rather stand in name of Acci\u00f3n Castellana.<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 13.02.31, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000352443&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In April 1931 he was elected president of [[:es:Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria|Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico-Agraria]], the nationwide agricultural organization.<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 180</ref>\n\n==Republic: in Cortes==\n{{CSS image crop\n|Image = Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac.jpg\n|bSize = 220\n|cWidth = 160\n|cHeight = 240\n|oTop = 30\n|oLeft = 40\n|Location = left\n|Description = Lamamie, 1930s\n}}\nAs representative of Acci\u00f3n Castellana Lamami\u00e9 joined a [[Electoral Carlism (Second Republic)|general right-wing alliance]]<ref> Acci\u00f3n Castellano was a satelite of Acci\u00f3n Nacional, the latter generally dominated by the Alfonsinos and accidentalists; Integrist presence in the organisation was a bit of an exception, Antonio M. Moral Roncal, ''La cuesti\u00f3n religiosa en la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola: Iglesia y carlismo'', Madrid 2009, {{ISBN|9788497429054}}, p. 50; similar comments in Vincent 1991, p. 191</ref> and was comfortably elected to the [[Spanish general election, 1931|first Republican Cortes]] from his Salamanca.<ref> see the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=1-1&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. here]</ref> In the chamber he joined the [[Spanish Agrarian Party|Agrarian block]];<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 126; one author claims that the Agrarian block \"distilled old monarchist wine into new republican bottles\", Vincent 1991, p. 221</ref> with 2 other Integrists<ref> dubbed \u201cintegrist trio\u201d; its other members were [[Francisco Est\u00e9vanez Rodr\u00edguez|Est\u00e9vanez Rodr\u00edguez]] and [[Ricardo G\u00f3mez Roji|G\u00f3mez Roji]], Blinkhorn 2008, p. 56</ref> he formed the right-wing<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 189</ref> or \u201cextreme right-wing\u201d of the grouping.<ref> Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 217</ref> As a Carlist he was re-elected from Salamanca<ref> initially Lamamie was supposed to run in the 1933 elections from Barcelona, Robert Vallverd\u00fa i Mart\u00ed, ''El carlisme catal\u00e0 durant la Segona Rep\u00fablica Espanyola 1931-1936'', Barcelona 2008, {{ISBN|9788478260805}}, p. 146</ref> in [[Spanish general election, 1933|1933]]<ref> see the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=2-2&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. here]</ref> and [[Spanish general election, 1936|1936]]; in the latter case the ticket was annulled<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 289; see also the official Cortes service, available [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXD1S.fmt&DOCS=3-3&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&NUM1=&DES1=&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. here]</ref> with his engagement in negotiation of government grain contracts quoted as incompatible with electoral law.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 231</ref> The 5 years spend in the Cortes marked the climax of Lamami\u00e9\u2019s career; though member of minor groupings, he became a nationally recognizable figure due to his oratory skills, vehemence and engagement in heated plenary debates. His parliamentary career was marked by two threads: opposition to republican agrarian policy and opposition to advanced secular format of the state.\n\nLamami\u00e9<ref> allegedly with Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Gil Robles Lamamie was one of \u201cdos personajes de enorme relevancia en el campo pol\u00edtico conservador\u201d in the province; Blinkhorn 2008, p. 65</ref> \u201cemerged as the most ardent Catholic opponent of state interference with the distribution of landed property\u201d<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 65</ref> and did his best to block the agrarian reform;<ref> Francisco Javier Lamb\u00e1n Monta\u00f1\u00e9s, ''La reforma agraria republicana en Arag\u00f3n, 1931-1936'' [PhD Universidad de Zaragoza], Zaragoza 2014, p. 74</ref> some count him among \u201cdefensores a ultranza de las viejas estructuras territoriales\u201d.<ref> opinion of Manuel Tu\u00f1on de Lara, ''Objectivo: acabar con la Rep\u00fablica'', [in:] ''SBHAC'' service, available [http://www.sbhac.net/Republica/TextosIm/Otros/Conspiracion/Conspiracion.htm here] </ref> Though Lamami\u00e9 recognized the need to sanate the rural regime following \u201ca century of rural liberalism\u201d, he thought the republican law an over-reaction, \u201can even worse doctrine which converts us all into slaves of the state\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 79</ref> Especially in 1933-1935 he labored to loosen already adopted rural regulations like the law on [[:es:Primer bienio de la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola|jurados mixtos]] or the Rural Lease Act.<ref> Sergio Riesco Roche, ''La lucha por la tierra: reformismo agrario y cuesti\u00f3n yuntera en la provincia de C\u00e1ceres'' [PhD thesis Complutense], Madrid 2005, p. 340</ref> Though he lambasted alleged ''[[Etatism|etatisme]]'' of [[Manuel Gim\u00e9nez Fern\u00e1ndez|Gim\u00e9nez Fern\u00e1ndez]],<ref> Lamami\u00e9 vehemently opposed cutting down minimum prices of wheat and blamed speculators, not producers, for high market prices </ref> at times he swallowed his \u201cdislike of state intervention\u201d and demanded governmental assistance by purchases of wheat surplus.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 195</ref> Lamami\u00e9 gained notoriety when left-wing newspapers quoted his declaration that he would turn a [[Schismatic (religion)|schismatic]] rather than accept land reform in case it gets supported by the Church;<ref> his alleged statement which made rounds across all Spain was that \u201csi not quitan las tierras, nos haremos cism\u00e1ticos\u201d; another version is that when told that \"habr\u00eda que poner en marcha medidas en el agro que siguieran la doctrina social de la Iglesia\", Lamami\u00e9 replied that \"antes se hac\u00eda cism\u00e1tico\", both versions repeated after Lamb\u00e1n Monta\u00f1\u00e9s 2014</ref> the claim is referred in literature as a proof of Lamami\u00e9\u2019s hypocrisy,<ref> Lamb\u00e1n Monta\u00f1\u00e9s 2014, p. 74</ref> but some claim it was fabricated by hostile propaganda.<ref>V\u00edctor Manuel Arbeloa Muru, ''\u201eSi nos quitan las tierras, not haremos cism\u00e1ticos\u201d'', [in:] ''Preg\u00f3n'' 53 (2019), pp. 34-35</ref> The member of radical right-wing among the Agrarians, also among the Carlists he stood as \u201clast-ditch defender of property\u201d<ref> though Lamamie is usually presented as fierce opponent of Republican agrarian reform, he was equally hostile versus the rural regime as endorsed by syndicalist revolutionaries of the Falange, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 124</ref> against left-leaning party parliamentarians like Gin\u00e9s Martinez Rubio.<ref> G\u00ednes Mart\u00ednez is presented with some irony \u2013 perhaps aimed to question sincerity of his zeal \u2013 as \u201cproletarian hammer of the selfish capitalist\u201d, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 124. One scholar claims, however, that politicians like Lamamie \"posed effectively as the true defenders of the people\", Vincent 1991, p. 355</ref>\n[[File:Congreso de los Diputados (Espa\u00f1a) 15.jpg|thumb|parliament building (present view)]]\nAnother major focus of Lamami\u00e9 as a deputy were religious issues.<ref>the Lamamie family was zealously Catholic. During the Republic days, when religious public rallies were generally illegal save for specific permits, on the private Lamamie estate they organized pilgrimages and romerias, at times attracting thousands of attendees, Vincent 1991, p. 134. The author mentions a \"Juan Lamamie\" as organizer</ref> He vehemently supported confessionality of state and claimed that \u201cGod comes first, and not merely relegated to the privacy of conscience\u201d.<ref>\u201clo primero es Dios, pero no relegado a la intimidad de la conciencia, como ahora es modo sostener, sino a quien no concebimos sino informandolo todo: el individuo, la familia, la sociedad, las costumbres, las leyes, la moral y el derecho\u201d, quoted after Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 270</ref> During the constitutional debate of 1931 he ardently opposed stipulations he considered oppressive and unjust versus the Catholics,<ref>\"within the Cortes and such unlikely champions of democracy as Lamamie de Clairac and Gil Robles, together with their fell ow Agrarians, the priest-deputies Gomez Rojf and Molina Nieto, were to be heard speaking the language of liberty, equality and civil rights\", Vincent 1991, pp. 239-240</ref> warning that if the state turns against them, they \u201cshall have no other remedy than to move against the Republic\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 66, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 54. Reportedly that was \"at the instigation of Lamamie\" that the Agrarians, the Traditionalists and the Basques withdrew from the Cortes in protest during voting on the constitutional draft, Vincent 1991, p. 242</ref> Lamami\u00e9 dedicated not one of his harangues to defend the Jesuits, the order marked for forcible dissolution; he tried to dismantle the republican narrative of the famous Jesuit \u201cfourth vow\u201d<ref> Lamamie claimed that only some 25% of the Jesuits took the famous \u201cfourth vow\u201d of obedience to the pope, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 78</ref> and lambasted the draft not only as inhuman, but also as non-constitutional;<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 61</ref> his campaign<ref>reinforced by ''La Gaceta Regional'', a Salamanca daily purchased in 1932 by a consortium of local businessmen, led by Lamamie, Vincent 1991, p. 156</ref> lasted until 1933, but proved fruitless.<ref> in May 1933 Lamamie unleashed his fury against the draft of the Law on Congregations; he declared it as aimed against God and openly claimed that it should be disobeyed, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 104</ref> Numerous timed denied the right to speak,<ref> e.g. in 1932 the speaker did not allow Lamamie to take to the floor and speak in defence of the Jesuits. He found an unexpected ally in the person of Miguel de Unamuno, who came to his help and claimed he had the right to speak, Alfonso Carlos Saiz Valdivielso, ''Don Miguel de Unamuno, un disidente ante las Cortes Constituyentes de la Segunda Rep\u00fablica'', [in:] ''Estudios de Deusto'' 51/1 (2003), p. 333</ref> he later got his parliamentary addresses published as a booklet.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 62</ref> During the [[:es:Segundo bienio de la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola|1933-1936 term]], dominated by the Right, he demanded nothing less than derogation of the constitutional article which defined the Republic as a secular state.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 180</ref>\n\n==Republic: in Carlist executive==\n[[File:M\u00edting del del Cercle Tradicionalista.jpeg|thumb|left|Carlist gathering, 1930s]]\nLamami\u00e9 entered the Republican parliament as an Integrist associated with Salamantine agrarian and generic right-wing circles,<ref> e.g. during the 1931 electoral campaign he toured the Salamanca province with Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Gil Robles, then rather unknown aspiring right-wing politician, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 100</ref> but already in late 1931 he was at odds with local conservatives.<ref> already in November 1931 Lamami\u00e9 was at odds with local conservatives; despite his position of the local parliamentarian he did not speak at their rallies. Background of the conflict is not entirely clear; apart from controversies related to reportedly appeasing conservative stand versus the Republic there might have been personal issues involved, Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez 2015, p. 53</ref> Instead, like most Integrists he started to approach the Carlists<ref>one scholar names Lamamie \"lifelong supporter of the Carlist pretender to the throne\", Vincent 1991, p. 180. However, there is no information available on his support for the Carlist claim prior to 1931</ref> and was leaning towards reunification of all Traditionalist branches.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 73</ref> The project was complete in early 1932, when they merged in [[Traditionalist Communion|Comuni\u00f3n Tradicionalista]].<ref>it seems that though member of the Carlist organization, until dissolution of the Cortes in 1933 he used to form part of the Agrarian minority, Vincent 1991, p. 234</ref> Within the organisation Lamami\u00e9 entered its nationwide executive Junta Suprema and became secretary of the body;<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, pp. 77-78</ref> he was also double-hatting as regional Traditionalist jef\u00e9 in Le\u00f3n.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 79</ref> In 1933 latest he was put in charge of the propaganda section<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 70</ref> and reportedly contributed to change of Carlist image; the movement was no longer perceived as antiquated group of senile veterans but as a dynamic organization of young militants.<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 83</ref> Though at times speaking at public rallies,<ref> despite his role in the Carlist nationwide executive Lamami\u00e9 fairly rarely spoke on public rallies beyond his native Old Castile; one of such cases was the spring 1932 campaign in Catalonia, Vallverdu i Marti 2008, p. 101, C\u00e9sar Alcal\u00e1, ''D. Mauricio de Sivatte. Una biograf\u00eda pol\u00edtica (1901-1980)'', Barcelona 2001, {{ISBN|8493109797}}, p. 20</ref> he turned into \u201cthe most persuasive and accomplished Carlist orator\u201d in the Cortes.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 78</ref> He went well with older generation of leaders, especially the fellow landowner [[Tomas Dominguez Arevalo|Rodezno]], and following re-organisation of 1934 he entered not only the broad Junta Suprema Nacional, but also a much smaller governing body, Junta Delegada.<ref> Junta Delegada consisted of Rodezno, [[Victor Pradera Larumbe|Pradera]], Lamami\u00e9 and [[Jose Luis de Oriol y Uriguen|Oriol]], Blinkhorn 2008, p. 133, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 117</ref>\n\nAlready in the early 1930s Lamami\u00e9 worked with the fellow Integrist [[Manuel Fal Conde|Manuel Fal]]<ref>[Ana Mar\u00edn Fidalgo, Manuel M. Burgue\u00f1o], ''In memoriam. Manuel J. Fal Conde (1894-1975)'', Sevilla 1978, p. 25</ref> and reportedly claimed the latter would one day become the party leader.<ref> ''Pensamiento Alaves'' 25.01.38, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000035336&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Following growing disappointment with Rodezno\u2019s lead, in 1934 he and Manuel Senante floated the candidacy of Fal,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 137</ref> who indeed assumed the party jefatura. Under his command Lamami\u00e9 retained his position as head of propaganda<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 207, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 120; in line with his propaganda tasks, in 1935 co-ordinated activities of the Carlist press, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 275</ref> and in 1935 was nominated to Council of the Communion, an advisory body supposed to assist Fal.<ref> the Council consisted of [[Esteban Bilbao Egu\u00eda|Bilbao]], [[Luis Hernando de Larramendi y Ruiz|Larramendi]], [[Lorenzo Alier Cassi|Alier]], Senante and Lamamie, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 215, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 263</ref> Since the mid-1930s he was gradually replacing Rodezno as the Carlist parliamentary leader. In the party he was one of the central figures who \u201ccould be relied upon to bridge the gap between the Communion old and new establishments\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 229-230</ref>\n[[File:Mitin tradicionalista.jpeg|thumb|Lamami\u00e9 at Carlist rally, 1930s (1fL)]]\nThough some scholars admit that initially Lamami\u00e9 might have been willing to collaborate with the Republican authorities,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 60</ref> adopted \u201cuna postura suave y conciliadora\u201d and only after 1933 turned into \u201cintegrista furibundo\u201d,<ref> J. M. Castells, ''Las asociaciones religiosas en la Espa\u00f1a contemporanea'', Madrid 1973, p. 394</ref> they note that it did not take long before he started to view the Republic as a tyrannical regime<ref> in the aftermath of sanurjada and in midsts of ensuing governmental repressions Lamami\u00e9 \u201cwas typical in belabouring the government for stepping up its \u2018tyrannical\u2019 behaviour by means of indiscriminate arrests, suspensions, closures, expropriations and deportations\u201d, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 93</ref> to be toppled sooner or later.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 66, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 54 </ref> He considered democracy incompatible with \"people's rights\".<ref>\"la democracia pol\u00edtica es la negaci\u00f3n efectiva de los derechos del pueblo\", quoted after Mar\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n Marcos del Olmo, ''Cultura de la violencia y Parlamento: los diputados Castellanos y Leoneses en las Cortes de 1936'', [in:] ''Diacronie'' 7 (2011), p. 9 </ref> Since late 1931 he was increasingly critical of right-wing politics guided by the \u201clesser evil\u201d principle and hence abandoned Acci\u00f3n Castellana in late 1932.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 101-102</ref> Since then he scorned [[CEDA]] for illusions about rectifying the Republic<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 129-130</ref> and in 1934 claimed that the CEDA-backed government<ref> in late 1932 and early 1933 Lamami\u00e9 declared that Carlism would never collaborate with any republican government, this is neither with a right-wing one, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 103</ref> gave in to [[Alejandro Lerroux|Lerroux]] and the Left.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 187. During the tenure of the right-wing government Lamamie was fully aware and approving of few Carlist militants being sent to Rome to receive military training with a view of a future violent overthrow of the Republic, Vincent 1991, p. 297</ref> In 1935 he engaged in virulent press polemics with his former prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Jose Maria Gil Robles Quinones|Gil Robles]]<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 192</ref> and was denounced by ''[[El Debate]]'' as running against the papal teaching;<ref> Moral Roncal 2009, p. 153</ref> in spite of it, in 1936 he half-heartedly assisted Fal in attempt to mount a right-wing electoral alliance.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 203</ref> While hostile to ''cedistas'' he was moderately<ref> in 1933 Lamamie was not very enthusiastic about a close co-operation with [[Renovaci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola]]; if so, it was to serve very limtied, pragmatic, electoral ends and in no way should it amount to any firm alliance, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 109</ref> in favor of a generic monarchist alliance within National Bloque.<ref> historiographic accounts tend to differ. One scholar counts Lamami\u00e9 among farily enthusiastic supporters of Bloque Nacional, see Blinkhorn 2008, p. 189; others are less definite, see Moral Roncal 2009, p. 125</ref> As former Integrist he was not outspoken on dynastical issues,<ref> e.g. in 1931 the Traditionalists were bewildered about a so-called Pact of Territet, an informal dynastical agreement allegedly sealed by Alfonso XIII and Don Jaime; it is difficult to tell from the accounts available what the position of Lamami\u00e9 was, Blinkhorn 2008, pp. 72, 322</ref> though he stayed fully within limits of the Carlist loyalty.<ref> one of the rare cases when Lamami\u00e9 engaged in dynastical propaganda during the Republc era was his co-edition of a 1935 document, signed by a few Carlist leaders. Following the wedding of the Alfonsist infant Don Juan, the document denied any rights to the throne either to Don Juan or to his future offspring, Moral Roncal 2009, p. 208</ref>\n\n==Conspirator and rebel==\n[[File:Jose Maria Lamamie de Clairac y Alonso.jpg|thumb|160px|left|son as [[requet\u00e9]]<ref>blown up by a grenade during fightings in Sierra de Guadarrama in February 1937. Four months earlier, his father called upon the young men to \"sacrifice your lives on the altar of ... traditional Spain\", quoted after Vincent 1991, pp. 348-349</ref>]]\nSince the electoral triumph of [[Popular Front (Spain)|Popular Front]] in February 1936 Lamami\u00e9 was increasingly perplexed about perceived revolutionary tide and inclined towards mounting a counter-action. In the early spring he \u201cnursed a longing for a purely Carlist rising\u201d,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 238</ref> prepared but eventually abandoned by the Comuni\u00f3n executive. However, he remained heavily engaged in conspiracy;<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2008, p. 296, Jordi Canal, ''El carlismo. Dos siglos de contrarrevoluci\u00f3n en Espa\u00f1a'', Madrid 2000, {{ISBN|9788420639475}}, p. 324</ref> together with dynastical representative [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Don Javier]] and Manuel Fal he formed a triumvirate which co-ordinated works of all sections of the organization.<ref> Juan Carlos Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo de Quir\u00f3s, ''El Carlismo, la Rep\u00fablica y la Guerra Civil (1936-1937). De la conspiraci\u00f3n a la unificaci\u00f3n'', Madrid 1996, {{ISBN|8487863523}}, p. 19; Julio Ar\u00f3stegui, ''Combatientes Requet\u00e9s en la Guerra Civil espa\u00f1ola, 1936-1939'', Madrid 2013, {{ISBN|9788499709758}}, p. 99</ref> Though he did not speak with military conspirators, he negotiated with Gil Robles; as late as on July 12 in [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]] the two fruitlessly discussed CEDA\u2019s access to the [[Spanish coup of July 1936|coup]].<ref> Ar\u00f3stegui 2013, p. 117</ref> It is not clear where Lamami\u00e9 resided on July 18-19, yet it is known that his wife and some sons remained in Madrid.<ref> Lamami\u00e9\u2019s wife and children trapped in Madrid following some time found refuge in foreign diplomatic missions and eventually made it to the Nationalist zone; for recollections of verious members of the Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac family, including these residing in Madrid, see Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Alonso 1991, pp. 19-101</ref>\n\nOn July 26 Lamami\u00e9 delivered an address broadcast by the Burgos radio;<ref> ''Heraldo de Zamora'' 27.07.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2257365&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> he called to support \"sacrosant crusade\" against \"horde of evil-doers at the service of Russia\".<ref>Vincent 1991, p. 343, though it is not sure whether the phrases quoted were not broadcast during a later, August Lamamie speech</ref> In response his Madrid bank account was seized<ref> ''La Libertad'' 20.08.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000201979&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and Republican press claimed a [[machine gun]] and loads of ammunition had been found in his [[safety deposit box]].<ref> ''Heraldo de Castell\u00f3n'' 20.08.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000384168&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> During August he toured various cities in Northern Castile encouraging recruitment<ref> ''Pensamiento Alaves'' 08.08.36, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000033664&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and visiting requet\u00e9 units.<ref> Ar\u00f3stegui 2013, p. 632</ref> In September he entered the newly formed wartime party executive Junta Nacional Carlista de Guerra as its secretary.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 22</ref> With his office based in Burgos, Lamami\u00e9 was also entrusted with recruitment and deployment of requet\u00e9.<ref> Ar\u00f3stegui 2013, p. 647</ref> He seemed to have stood in-between Fal Conde and somewhat autonomous [[Navarre|Navarrese]] command, Junta Central Carlista. Some authors claim he was among Fal\u2019s less dependable trustees,<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 269</ref> though this enabled him to engage in some fence-mending between the two Carlist Juntas.<ref> e.g. in early December 1936, following Fal Conde\u2019s decision to set a Carlist-only military academy, Lamami\u00e9 travalled to Pamplona to discuss with the local executive the details of setting up and the institution and organizing its teaching staff; one historian views the move as sort of an olive branch offered to the Navarrese Junta by Fal and the central Junta, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 237</ref> When Fal was forced to go on exile the power in the party technically rested with [[Jose Maria Valiente Soriano|Valiente]] and Lamami\u00e9, though in fact it slipped to traditional leaders from Navarre and the [[Names of the Basque Country (in Spanish)|Vascongadas]].<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 278</ref> In December he was confirmed as member of the re-organized 8-member Junta Nacional.<ref> it consisted of Fal Conde, Rodezno, Lamami\u00e9, Valiente, [[Juan S\u00e1enz-D\u00edez Garc\u00eda|S\u00e1enz-D\u00edez]], Mu\u00f1oz Aguilar, [[Jose Maria Arauz de Robles Estremera|Arauz de Robles]] and Zamanillo, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 241</ref> He cultivated the usual propaganda tasks,<ref>see e.g. his 1937 appearance in Palencia, ''El D\u00eda de Palencia'' 07.01.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2199538&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here], or in Zamora, ''Imperio'' 08.02.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000117448&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> but was entrusted also with running Secci\u00f3n Administrativa.<ref> the Carlist executive was territorially dispersed; in late 1936 and early 1937 Lamami\u00e9 and his Secci\u00f3n Administrativa were based in Burgos; Fal Conde and his collaborators were based in Toledo; Rodezno and Secci\u00f3n Pol\u00edtica resided in Salamanca, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 238</ref>\n[[File:Tropas del bando nacional (14 de 16) - Fondo Mar\u00edn-Kutxa Fototeka.jpg|thumb|requet\u00e9, 1937]]\nLamami\u00e9 was increasingly puzzled by the emerging [[Francisco Franco|Franco\u2019s]] heavy-handed rule. In early 1937 he intervened with [[Fidel D\u00e1vila Arrondo|general D\u00e1vila]] to get Fal Conde released from exile; the plea was to no avail.<ref> Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 243</ref> In February he took part in the crucial [[Insua]] meeting, where Carlist leaders and their regent discussed the threat of military-imposed political amalgamation. His stand is not clear;<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 283, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 46</ref> highly skeptical about forced unification, he did not voice decisively against it,<ref> Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, pp. 257, 263</ref> which did not spare him particular personal animadversion in the Franco headquarters.<ref> in early 1937 particular \u201canimadversaci\u00f3n\u201d in the Franco\u2019s headquarters was directed at Lamami\u00e9, Zamanillo and Araiz de Robles, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 267</ref> One contemporary historian counts him among \u201ctwo of the most persistent fence-sitters\u201d<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 287; the other one was allegedly Arauz de Robles</ref> and another locates him \u201centre un polo y el otro\u201d of the Carlist command layer. In early April he engaged in fruitless last-minute talks with [[Falange Espa\u00f1ola de las JONS|Falangist]] leaders, staged to agree a bottom-up alliance.<ref> Fidaldo, Burgue\u00f1o 1980, p. 43, Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo 1996, p. 269</ref> Eventually when faced with the [[Unification Decree (Spain, 1937)|military unification dictate]] he grudgingly opted for compliance, assuming that in case something goes wrong, \u201cour Sacred Cause would always be reborn out of its own ashes\u201d.<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 291</ref>\n\n==Restless ''sansidrino''==\n[[File:Burgos 1937.jpg|thumb|left|in [[Burgos]], 1937 (2fR)]]\n[[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Don Javier]] considered Lamami\u00e9 fully loyal and authorized him to enter ruling bodies of the [[Falange Espanola Tradicionalista y de las JONS|unificated state party]],<ref> Blinkhorn 2008, p. 293</ref> but he preferred to tone down his political engagements. Instead, he resumed activity in agricultural organisations, in particular Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional Cat\u00f3lico Agraria, which he still presided. Because of its acronymic name CNCA, Lamami\u00e9 and other of its top lobbyists were named \"sansidrinos\".<ref> Javier T\u00e9bar Hurtado, ''Contrarrevoluci\u00f3n y poder agrario en el franquismo. Rupturas y continuidades. La provincia de Barcelona (1939-1945)'', [PhD thesis Universidad Autonoma], Barcelona 2005, p. 115</ref> Already in June 1937 they staged a grand Asamblea Cerealista in Valladolid;<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 23.06.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000474384&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> Lamami\u00e9 was confirmed in presidency of CNCA and president of one of its components, Confederaci\u00f3n Cat\u00f3lico Agraria. Relations with the emerging Francoist regime remained correct; the traditional confederative structure was affiliated within the newly established syndicalist [[:es:Servicio Nacional del Trigo|Servicio Nacional de Trigo]] and both organizations declared total mutual understanding.<ref> ''La Espiga'' 05.11.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467802&posicion=5&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> In late 1937 Lamami\u00e9 personally obtained some unspecified contracts in the Salamanca province<ref> ''El Adelanto'' 26.11.37, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000474517&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and in March 1938 the [[Ministry of the Interior (Spain)|Interior]] decree nominated him governor of the Burgos-based Banco de Cr\u00e9dito Local de Espa\u00f1a,<ref>some authors claim that already in 1919 Lamamie was president of \"the local [Salamanca] savings bank\", Vincent 1991, p. 165</ref> a bank entrusted with financial aid to municipalities taken over from the [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republicans]].<ref> ''Heraldo de Zamora'' 21.03.38, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2261943&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref>\n\nThroughout 1938 CNCA and the syndicalist Francoist administration were increasingly at a collision course, both advancing competitive visions of the rural regime.<ref> already during the Republican period Lamami\u00e9 voiced against fascism, which he equalled to a state dictate; he lambasted it as an imported theory not applicable to Spain, even though he saw some of its features \u2013 like \u201cemphasis upon hierarchy and combativeness\u201d \u2013 appropriate for Carlist paramilitary units, Blinkhorn 2008, p. 166</ref> The first battleground was [[Catalonia]], where on areas seized by the Nationalists the traditional local body, [[:es:Instituto Agr\u00edcola Catal\u00e1n de San Isidro|Instituto Agricola Catalan de San Isidro]], tried to reassert its domination. CNCA backed its claims and argued that they in no way interfered with officially declared vertical sindicates; a stalemate ensued.<ref> T\u00e9bar Hurtado 2005, pp. 112-113</ref> However, in October 1938 the government issued Ley de Cooperativas, which left the ''sansidrinos'' profoundly disappointed. In April 1939 CNCA demanded that clear rules of the newly established Servicio Nacional de Cooperativas get published and underlined that traditional rural organizations did not enter SNC awaiting the moment it is legally defined. Lamami\u00e9 issued declarations which in a veiled way warned against arbitrary ministerial decisions, advocated co-existence of state and private bodies, and called for recognition of 3-layer rural organizations.<ref>the 3-layer structure recommended by Lamami\u00e9 was to consist of 1) Sindicatos (to become Cooperativas), 2) Federaciones, and 3) nationaiwde Confederaci\u00f3n. His declarations of the time contained a hardly veiled criticism of Falangist syndicalism, compare ''La Espiga'' 06.05.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467867&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> During 1939 and 1940 CNCA claimed it could operate \u201csin rozar la funci\u00f3n de los Sindicatos verticales\u201d<ref> ''El Dia de Palencia'' 30.04.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=2206380&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> and fought marginalization.<ref>e.g. a CNCA document of October 1939 referred to earlier Francoist legislation on cooperatives, adopted on November 29, 1938, and in line with the January 28, 1906 legislation attempted to carve out a space within the rural regime where Catholic syndicated might operate, ''La Espiga'' 28.10.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467883&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here]</ref>\n[[File:Trilla 2.JPG|thumb|working the fields, early [[Francoism]]]]\nIn the early 1940s militant syndicalist Falangism enjoyed its climax in the Francoist Spain; it translated also into outcome of power struggle within the rural agricultural ambience. Despite repeated declarations of loyalty on part of CNCA and numerous assurances that in no way it posed a thread to syndical law,<ref> ''La Espiga'' 10.04.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467891&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> conservative and Christian agrarians were getting increasingly pushed into the sidelines; also Lamami\u00e9 lost steam and at one point admitted in relation to planned new regulations that \u201cno tuvo ning\u00fan reparo que objetas sino por el contario le pareci\u00f3 muy bien\u201d.<ref> T\u00e9bar Hurtado 2005, p. 186</ref> In September 1940 he left the CNCA presidency and declarations of their meeting with [[:es:Delegaci\u00f3n Nacional de Sindicatos|Delegaci\u00f3n Nacional de Sindicatos]] sounded like admitting defeat.<ref> ''El Progreso'' 06.09.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=3103081&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> With Lamami\u00e9 as honorary president<ref> ''La Espiga'' 24.12.42, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000467941&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> CNCA was ultimately dissolved and incorporated into the new Uni\u00f3n Nacional de Cooperativas del Campo in 1942.<ref> Emilio Majuelo, ''Falangistas y cat\u00f3lico-sociales en liza por el control de las cooperativas'', [in:] ''Historia del presente'' 3 (2004), p. 39</ref> Lamami\u00e9 kept presiding over Banco Exterior de Cr\u00e9dito Local de Espa\u00f1a at least until the early 1940s.<ref>''Heraldo de Zamora'' 17.02.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000116871&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here]; as late as in 1943 he was involved in dealings of the Salamanca ayuntamiento, but it is not clear whether he formed part of it, ''El Adelanto'' 18.12.43, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000476403&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina here]</ref>\n\n==Late Carlist activity==\n[[File:Flag of Cross of Burgundy.svg|thumbnail|left|Carlist standard]]\nAt the turn of the decades Lamami\u00e9 was barely noted officially for Carlist political activity,<ref>he was moderately engaged in Nationalist propaganda work, e.g. following takeover of Catalonia in 1939 he embarked on a tour there, ''Pensamiento Alaves'' 21.01.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000034818&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> though he did participate in Traditionalism-flavored religious services or other rallies.<ref>e.g. in August 1939 with some other Traditonalist militants \u2013 notably his fellow ex-Integrist Senante \u2013 he took part in religious service to employees of Editorial Tradicionalista who perished ruring the war, ''Lab\u00f3r'' 28.08.39, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=3028361&posicion=3&presentacion=pagina here]</ref> He used to take part in confidential meetings; in 1940 when returning from such a session with a [[Carlo-francoism|carlo-francoist]] general [[:es:Ricardo Rada|Ricardo Rada]] he suffered a car accident<ref> Manuel de Santa Cruz [Alberto Ruiz de Galarreta], ''Apuntes y documentos para la historia del tradicionalismo espa\u00f1ol: 1939-1966'', vols. 1-3, Seville 1979, p. 95</ref> and barely managed to dispose of related potentially damaging documentation before the [[Guardia Civil]] patrol arrived.<ref> ''Heraldo de Zamora'' 26.01.40, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000116852&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> The same year he corresponded with [[:es:Direcci\u00f3n General de Seguridad|Director General de Seguridad]] protesting repressions against Carlist militants;<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, p. 95</ref> on another front, he conferred about keeping the [[Alfonsism|Alfonsists]] in check.<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, p. 26</ref> In 1941 Lamami\u00e9 supplied Don Javier with his political analysis, but its content is not known.<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, p. 82</ref> During the climax of the [[Nazi]] might in Europe he advocated a neutral Spanish policy<ref> in a 1941 letter to Serrano Su\u00f1er Lamami\u00e9 quoted the case of Carlos VII, who assumed a neutral stand during the international 1898 crisis, and this of Jaime III, who advocated neutrality during the First World War </ref> and declared that individual Carlists were free to enlist to [[Divisi\u00f3n Azul]], but Comun\u00edon would in no way endorse the recruitment.<ref> Santa Cruz 1979, pp. 137-140</ref> In another letter, sent 1942, he protested to [[Ramon Serrano Suner|Ramon Serrano Serrano]] against official measures applied to Fal Conde.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 92</ref> In 1943 he co-signed a large document addressed to Franco and known as ''Reclamaci\u00f3n de Poder''; its Carlist signatories called to do away with syndicalist features and to introduce a traditionalist monarchy.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 96, Alcal\u00e1 2001, p. 52</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1940s Lamami\u00e9 was among moderate anti-Francoists; during a 1944 monarchist gathering which included also the Alfonsists he voted against mounting a coup, intended to topple the caudillo.<ref> Alcal\u00e1 2001, p. 57</ref> In 1947 he took part in the first meeting of Carlist executive since the 1937 Insua session and entered the re-established 5-member Consejo Nacional.<ref> the Council consisted of Fal Conde, Valiente, Zamanillo, Saenz-Diez and Lamami\u00e9, Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 106, Canal 2000, p. 350</ref> In support of the moderately anti-Francoist falcondista strategy he opposed the vehemently anti-Francoist [[Maurici de Sivatte i de Bobadilla|sivattista]] line, increasingly visible in the late 1940s.<ref> Alcal\u00e1 2001, pp. 72, 78</ref> In the early 1950s as secretary of the Carlist executive he prepared documentation supposed to back the royal claim of Don Javier, who until then had posed as a regent and did not advance explicit monarchical claims;<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 132</ref> he edited the final version of the declaration, made by the claimant during the Eucharistic Congress in [[Barcelona]] in 1952.<ref> Jacek Bartyzel, ''Nic bez Boga, nic wbrew tradycji'', Radzymin 2015, {{ISBN|9788360748732}}, p. 251</ref> At that time he was already suffering from bad health and in the early 1950s he used a wheelchair;<ref> ''Nueva Alcarr\u00eda'' 24.07.54, available [https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=5083114&posicion=1&presentacion=pagina here] </ref> however, in 1954 he accepted membership in the renewed party Junta Nacional and its acting governing body Comisi\u00f3n Permanente.<ref> Vallverdu i Mart\u00ed 2014, p. 138</ref> In the mid-1950s the Carlist stand versus the regime changed from opposition to cautious co-operation; it was sealed by dismissal of Fal Conde and by Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Valiente assuming political leadership. The latter still considered Lamami\u00e9 a loyal \u201chombre firme y en\u00e9rgico\u201d<ref> Mercedes V\u00e1zquez de Prada, ''El final de una ilusi\u00f3n. Auge y declive del tradicionalismo carlista (1957-1967)'', Madrid 2016, {{ISBN|9788416558407}}, pp. 40-41</ref> and sounded him upon assuming secretariat of the ruling party junta. In 1956 Lamami\u00e9 replied that though sick, he was ready to offer his name as \u201cuna garant\u00eda absoluta de defensa de la Causa\u201d;<ref> Mercedes V\u00e1zquez de Prada, ''El nuevo rumbo pol\u00edtico del carlismo hacia la colaboraci\u00f3n con el r\u00e9gimen (1955-56)'', [in:] ''Hispania'' 69 (2009), pp. 190-191</ref> his death came earlier.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Integrism (Spain)]]\n* [[Carlism]]\n* [[Traditionalism (Spain)]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Martin Blinkhorn, ''Carlism and Crisis in Spain 1931-1939'', Cambridge 2008, {{ISBN|9780521086349}}\n* Hermanos Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Alonso, ''Recuerdos de la guerra: Espa\u00f1a 1936-1939: vividos y relatados por los autores'', M\u00e9xico 1991, {{ISBN|9789688590317}}\n* Jes\u00fas Maldonado Jim\u00e9nez, ''Actitudes pol\u00edtico religiosas de la minor\u00eda agraria de las Cortes Constituyentes de 1931'' [PhD Universidad Complutense 1974], Madrid 2015\n* Emilio Majuelo Gil, ''Falangistas y cat\u00f3licos sociales en liza por el control de las cooperativas'', [in:] ''Historia del presente'' 3 (2004), pp. 29-43\n* Antonio M. Moral Roncal, ''La cuesti\u00f3n religiosa en la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Espa\u00f1ola: Iglesia y carlismo'', Madrid 2009, {{ISBN|9788497429054}}\n* Juan Carlos Pe\u00f1as Bernaldo de Quir\u00f3s, ''El Carlismo, la Rep\u00fablica y la Guerra Civil (1936-1937). De la conspiraci\u00f3n a la unificaci\u00f3n'', Madrid 1996, {{ISBN|8487863523}}\n* [[Antonio P\u00e9rez de Olaguer]], ''Piedras Vivas. Biografia del Capellan Requete Jose M. Lamamie de Clairac y Alonso'', Madrid 1939\n* Mary Vincent, ''Catholicism in the Second Spanish Republic: Religion and Politics in Salamanca, 1930-1936'', London 1996, {{ISBN|9780198206132}}\n[[File:Family of Lamamie de Clairac.jpg|thumb|with family, 1920s]]\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.geni.com/people/Jose-Maria-Lamamie-de-Clairac-y-de-la-Colina/6000000019299952895 Lamamie at ''Geni'' genealogical site]\n* [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDIndHistDip?_piref73_1340024_73_1340023_1340023.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXLDA.fmt&DOCS=1-125&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&QUERY=%2858860%29.NDIP. Lamamie at the official Cortes service]\n* {{YouTube|Es5PCrb2cTQ|''Para maior gl\u00f3ria de Deus'' - Brazilian homage to Lamamie's son}}\n* {{YouTube|uhK1ER3B4Hg|''Por Dios y por Espa\u00f1a''; contemporary Carlist propaganda}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamami\u00e9 de Clairac y Colina, Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda}}\n[[Category:Castilian-Leonese politicians]]\n[[Category:Carlists]]\n[[Category:Far-right politicians in Spain]]\n[[Category:People of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Salamanca]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic activists]]\n[[Category:Spanish anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Spanish landowners]]\n[[Category:Spanish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Spanish monarchists]]\n[[Category:National syndicalists]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of the Spanish Civil War (National faction)]]\n[[Category:Spanish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic activists]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Lamami%C3%A9_de_Clairac_y_Colina"}
{"title_page": "Roshan Ravindra", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Roshan Ravindra <br> \u0dbb\u0ddc\u0dc2\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dca \u0dbb\u0dc0\u0dd3\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\n| image = \n| caption = \n| nationality = [[Sri Lanka]]n\n| birth_date = \n| birth_name = Roshan Ravindra Rajapakse\n| spouse = Sanjeewani \n| children = 3\n| occupation = Actor, Producer\n| years_active = 2004\u2013present\n}}\n'''Roshan Ravindra Rajapakse''' (Sinhala: '''\u0dbb\u0ddc\u0dc2\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dca \u0dbb\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb''') is an [[actor]] in [[Cinema of Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan cinema]], theater and television.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfc.gov.lk/artist/roshan-ravindra-212/ | title=Roshan Ravindra | publisher=National Film Corporation Of Sri Lanka| accessdate=30 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://movietimes.lk/celebrity/\u0dbb\u0ddc\u0dc2\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dca-\u0dbb\u0dc0\u0dd3\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb/ | title=Actor Roshan Ravindra | publisher=movietimes | accessdate=30 July 2019}}</ref> Highly versatile actor particularly act in dramatic roles, Ravindra is a recipeint of Best Actor Award in many local award festivals.<ref name= bestactor>{{cite web|last1=Thilakasiri|first1=Sameera|title=16th Sumathi Awards 2011|url=http://www.sandeshaya.org/16th-sumathi-awards-2011/|website=Sandeshaya dedicated to Sri Lankan Sinhala films, movies, cinema...|date=22 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nominations for Raigam Tele\u2019es  {{!}} The Sundaytimes Sri Lanka|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/130512/magazine/nominations-for-raigam-telees-43894.html|work=www.sundaytimes.lk}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRavindra is married to Sanjeewani, and they have a son Nethruu and daughter Kethaki.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sarasaviya.lk/2013/01/10/?fn=sa13011010|title=Chat with Roshan|publisher=Sarasaviya |accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> He is a disciple of Sri Lankan actor [[Mahendra Perera]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=lanka|first1=Gossip|title=Mahendra Perera likes to act with Sunny Leone|url=http://www.gossiplankahotnews.com/2014/06/mahendra-perera-likes-to-act-with-sunny.html|work=www.gossiplankahotnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBefore acting, he worked as a make-up artist in some films such as ''Sudu Kalu Saha Alu''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/061210/TV/002_10_12_2006.html | title=Sanath performs director's role | publisher=Sunday Times| accessdate=30 July 2019}}</ref> His most popular television acting came through ''Uthuwan Kande Sura Saradiyal'' as title role,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://archives.sundayobserver.lk/2006/09/10/mag03.asp | title=Saradiel re-lived | publisher=Sunday Observer | accessdate=30 July 2019}}</ref> and then in ''Sahodaraya''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.asianmirror.lk/entertainment/item/25878-namal-jayasinghe-s-sahodaraya-from-november | title=Namal Jayasinghe's 'Sahodaraya' From November | publisher=Asian Mirror| accessdate=30 July 2019}}</ref>  His first project as a television producer was the teledrama ''Rasthiyadukaraya'' Directed by Lakmini Amaradewa,<ref>{{cite news|title=Roshan ravindra, Roshan ravindra in sri lanka|url=http://www.gossip7.info/hot_lanka/show.php?id=3080#.WJM_TdJ94dU|work=www.gossip7.info}}</ref> followed by ''Kadadora'' directed by Rajiv Ananda.<ref>{{cite news|title=roshan ravindra, Roshan Ravindra in sri lanka|url=http://www.sithma.com/hot_lanka/show.php?id=2823#.WDGkz9J94dU|work=www.sithma.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 he directed his maiden television serial ''Thanamalvila Kollek''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dinamina.lk/2020/02/18/\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0dc1\u0dda\u0dc2\u0dcf\u0d82\u0d9c/90477/\u0db8\u0dda-\u0db8\u0ddc\u0dc4\u0ddc\u0dad-\u0d85\u0db7\u0dd2\u0dba\u0ddd\u0d9c\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dca\u0db8\u0d9a\u0dba\u0dd2p | title=This moment is challenging | publisher=Dinamina | accessdate=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Selected television serials===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* ''Aebarthu Aetha'' '\n* ''Ahasin Watuna'' 