{"title_page": "Vansire", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = Vansire\n| image               = Vansire.jpg\n| caption             = Vansire\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Dream Pop]]|[[Bedroom Pop]]|[[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]}}\n| years_active        = 2015-present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Spirit Goth Records\n* Driftless Recordings\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|FLOOR CRY|Chester Watson|[[sophie meiers]]|[[Jeremiah Jae]]}}\n| website             = https://vansire.bandcamp.com/music\n| current_members     = Josh Augustin<br/>Sam Winemiller\n}}\n'''Vansire''' is a [[dream pop]]/[[bedroom pop]] band from Rochester, Minnesota, USA, created by Josh Augustin and Sam Winemiller. Augustin says the band initially met in high school drumline, both being \"band geeks to the fullest extent\", and quickly became friends.<ref name=\"Oberlin\">{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Bed |title=Q&A with Vansire Cofounder Josh Augustin \u201920 |url=https://www.oberlin.edu/news/qa-vansire-cofounder-josh-augustin-20|website=Oblerlin College and Conservatory |publisher=Oberlin College and Conservatory |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The band released their initial single \"Bridges for the Young\" on August 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bridges for the young. |url=https://vansire.bandcamp.com/album/bridges-for-the-young |website=Bandcamp |publisher=Bandcamp |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> From 2015 onward, the band enjoyed a steady gain in fame and notability, and as of April 2020, 30+ million streams on Spotify.<ref name=\"spotify\">{{cite web |title=Vansire |url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/6ft7JnxMyZhp7N52qzHymY |website=Spotify |publisher=Spotify}}</ref>\n\n== Sound ==\nVansire describe themselves as a \"Dream-Pop\" band.<ref name=\"Oberlin\" /> Augustin described the development of their sound as not something intentional but reflective of both what they listen to and their lives.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anthony |first1=Dominic |title=Q&A: Josh Augustin of Vansire |url=http://www.krtuindie.org/blog/2018/12/3/qampa-josh-augustin |website=IndieOverNite91.7 |publisher=KRTUIndie |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> They have previously cited inspirations such as [[Mac Demarco]], [[Tame Impala]], [[Washed Out]], and [[Melody's Echo Chamber]].<ref name=\"Rochester\">{{cite web |title=ROCKchester festival preview: Interview with Josh Augustin of Vansire |url=https://www.medcitybeat.com/news-blog/2016/rockchester-festival-preview-interview-with-josh-augustin-of-vansire |website=MedCity Beat |publisher=Med City Beat |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\nVansire is composed of Josh Augustin on Vocals, Synths, Guitar and Drums and Sam Winemiller on Bass, Guitar and Synths.<ref name=\"Oberlin\" /> Sam's younger brother, Isaac, also plays bass on some tracks.<ref name=\"spotify\" /> Isaac is also part of their live group, which also includes Nathan Richter and Jake Johnson.<ref name=\"Rochester\" />\n\n== Name ==\nThe name \"Vansire\" is a reference to a species of [[Mongoose]] and a species of Parasitic Wasp, and after Sam was bitten by a wasp, the two were inspired to choose a name along the lines of wasps and mongooses.<ref name=\"Rochester\" />\n\n== Discography ==\n'''Albums'''\n* Angel Youth (2018)\n* Reflections and Reveries (2016)\n'''Singles and EP's'''\n* Metamodernity (2019)\n* That I Miss you (2018)\n* Star Catcher (2018)\n* Halcyon Age (2017)\n* Brown Study (2017)\n* The Rolling Driftless North (2017)\n* Driftless (2017)\n* Pontchartrain (2016)\n* Postal Codes (2016)\n* Bridges for the Young (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* https://vansire.bandcamp.com/\n* https://soundcloud.com/vansire-624239522\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Dream pop musical groups]]\n[[Category:Bedroom pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Musical groups with year of establishment missing]]\n\n\n{{US-pop-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = Vansire\n| image               = Vansire Promotional.jpg\n| caption             = Vansire\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Dream Pop]]|[[Bedroom Pop]]|[[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]}}\n| years_active        = 2015-present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Spirit Goth Records\n* Driftless Recordings\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|FLOOR CRY|Chester Watson|[[sophie meiers]]|[[Jeremiah Jae]]}}\n| website             = https://vansire.bandcamp.com/music\n| current_members     = Josh Augustin<br/>Sam Winemiller\n}}\n'''Vansire''' is a [[dream pop]]/[[bedroom pop]] band from Rochester, Minnesota, USA, created by Josh Augustin and Sam Winemiller. Augustin says the band initially met in high school drumline, both being \"band geeks to the fullest extent\", and quickly became friends.<ref name=\"Oberlin\">{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Bed |title=Q&A with Vansire Cofounder Josh Augustin \u201920 |url=https://www.oberlin.edu/news/qa-vansire-cofounder-josh-augustin-20|website=Oblerlin College and Conservatory |publisher=Oberlin College and Conservatory |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The band released their initial single \"Bridges for the Young\" on August 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bridges for the young. |url=https://vansire.bandcamp.com/album/bridges-for-the-young |website=Bandcamp |publisher=Bandcamp |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> From 2015 onward, the band enjoyed a steady gain in fame and notability, and as of April 2020, 30+ million streams on Spotify.<ref name=\"spotify\">{{cite web |title=Vansire |url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/6ft7JnxMyZhp7N52qzHymY |website=Spotify |publisher=Spotify}}</ref>\n\n== Sound ==\nVansire describe themselves as a \"Dream-Pop\" band.<ref name=\"Oberlin\" /> Augustin described the development of their sound as not something intentional but reflective of both what they listen to and their lives.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anthony |first1=Dominic |title=Q&A: Josh Augustin of Vansire |url=http://www.krtuindie.org/blog/2018/12/3/qampa-josh-augustin |website=IndieOverNite91.7 |publisher=KRTUIndie |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> They have previously cited inspirations such as [[Mac Demarco]], [[Tame Impala]], [[Washed Out]], and [[Melody's Echo Chamber]].<ref name=\"Rochester\">{{cite web |title=ROCKchester festival preview: Interview with Josh Augustin of Vansire |url=https://www.medcitybeat.com/news-blog/2016/rockchester-festival-preview-interview-with-josh-augustin-of-vansire |website=MedCity Beat |publisher=Med City Beat |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\nVansire is composed of Josh Augustin on Vocals, Synths, Guitar and Drums and Sam Winemiller on Bass, Guitar and Synths.<ref name=\"Oberlin\" /> Sam's younger brother, Isaac, also plays bass on some tracks.<ref name=\"spotify\" /> Isaac is also part of their live group, which also includes Nathan Richter and Jake Johnson.<ref name=\"Rochester\" />\n\n== Name ==\nThe name \"Vansire\" is a reference to a species of [[Mongoose]] and a species of Parasitic Wasp, and after Sam was bitten by a wasp, the two were inspired to choose a name along the lines of wasps and mongooses.<ref name=\"Rochester\" />\n\n== Discography ==\n'''Albums'''\n* Angel Youth (2018)\n* Reflections and Reveries (2016)\n'''Singles and EP's'''\n* Metamodernity (2019)\n* That I Miss you (2018)\n* Star Catcher (2018)\n* Halcyon Age (2017)\n* Brown Study (2017)\n* The Rolling Driftless North (2017)\n* Driftless (2017)\n* Pontchartrain (2016)\n* Postal Codes (2016)\n* Bridges for the Young (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* https://vansire.bandcamp.com/\n* https://soundcloud.com/vansire-624239522\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Dream pop musical groups]]\n[[Category:Bedroom pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Musical groups with year of establishment missing]]\n\n\n{{US-pop-band-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Post-Cultural", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vansire"}
{"title_page": "List of comedy television series with LGBT characters", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{dynamic list}}\n{{sp}}\n{{hatnote|This article is about  '''[[live action]]''' [[comedy]] television programs. [[Comedy-drama]]s (aka dramedy) are also included in [[List of dramatic television series with LGBT characters]]. For <u>[[animated cartoon|animated]]</u> series, see [[List of animated series with LGBT characters]].}}\n\nThis is a list of '''[[television comedy|comedy television series]]'''  (including [[miniseries]] and [[web television]]) which feature [[lesbian]], [[Male homosexuality|gay]], [[bisexual]], [[transgender]], [[Asexuality|asexual]], [[Gray asexuality|graysexual]], [[non-binary]] and [[Pansexuality|pansexual]]  [[Character (arts)|characters]]. The orientation can be portrayed on-screen, described in the [[dialogue]] or mentioned.\n\n==1970s==\n<!--Using Visual Editor: please be very careful when using VE. VE is problematic with tables. See [[WP:VE]] > Limitations-->\n<!--[[WP:VERIFY]]: \"All material in Wikipedia mainspace, including everything in articles, lists and captions, must be verifiable.\"-->\n<!--Please include citations from [[WP:RELIABLE]] sources that support addition of characters to this list.-->\n<!--If you are unsure of how to properly cite a source, open \"Cite\" on the [[Wikipedia:RefToolbar]] and select a Template. Click [Show/hide extra fields] button to open \"Date\" (i.e. date published), \"Archive\", and additional parameters.-->\n<!--LGBT characters are also listed by orientation in [[List of LGBT characters in television and radio]].-->\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margins:auto; width=100%;\"\n! style=\"width:75px;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:225px;\"|Show\n! style=\"width:100px\"|Network\n! style=\"width:200px\"|Character\n! style=\"width:200px\"|Actor\n! style=\"width:500px;\"|Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1972\u20131973 || {{hs|Corner Bar}}''[[The Corner Bar]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || Peter Panama || [[Vincent Schiavelli]] || The first continuing portrayal of a gay person on American television.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sparta|first=Christine|title=Emergence from the closet|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/2002/2002-03-11-coming-out-timeline.htm|work=USA Today|date=March 11, 2002|accessdate=6 December 2008}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1972\u20131985 || ''[[Are You Being Served?]]'' || [[BBC]] || [[Mr. Humphries]] || [[John Inman]] || British sitcom about staff working in the Grace Brothers department store. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1975 || ''[[Hot l Baltimore]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || George <br /> Gordon || [[Lee Bergere]] <br /> [[Henry Calvert]] || The first gay couple on American network television. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1975\u20131982 || ''[[Barney Miller]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || Marty Morrison <br /> Darryl Driscoll <br /> Officer Zatelli || [[Jack DeLeon]] <br /> [[Ray Stewart (actor)|Ray Stewart]] <br /> [[Dino Natali]] || Marty was a semi-regular on the long-running television series and Darryl made several appearances as Marty's lover. Series creator [[Danny Arnold]] worked closely with the National Gay Task Force in developing the characters of Darryl and Marty. Initially both were presented as flamboyantly gay men, but as the series progressed Darryl began acting and dressing more conservatively.<ref>{{cite web|last=Capsuto|first=Steven|title=U.S. Television: 1970\u20131975 (click on link Barney Miller)|url=http://www.stevecap.com/alternatechannels_net/us/19701975.htm|accessdate=2009-02-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716135741/http://www.stevecap.com/alternatechannels_net/us/19701975.htm|archive-date=2011-07-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> Officer Zatelli's coming out, initially to Captain Miller but eventually to the entire squad, was the first gay-themed [[story arc]] on American television and Arnold again worked with the NGTF to develop it. <br> {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1976\u20131977 || ''[[Mary Hartman, Mary Hartman]]'' || [[Broadcast syndication|Syndicated]] || Ed McCullough<br />Howard McCullough || [[Laurence Haddon]]<br />Beeson Carroll || Ed and Howard were introduced as a pair of brothers sharing a house in the Hartmans' neighborhood but were later revealed to be a gay couple hoping to live an open life in Fernwood. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1976 (unaired) || ''[[Snip (TV series)|Snip]]'' || [[NBC]] || Michael || Walter Wanderman || He was the owner of the salon where the characters worked. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1976 || {{hs|Nancy Walker Show}}''[[The Nancy Walker Show]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || Terry Folson || [[Ken Olfson]] || Terry was an out-of-work actor and personal assistant to lead character Nancy Kitteridge ([[Nancy Walker]]). {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1976 || ''[[Ball Four (TV series)|Ball Four]]'' || [[CBS]] || Unnamed || || Based on the book ''[[Ball Four]]''. Featured a gay rookie baseball player.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Frutkin|first1=Alan|last2=Kroll|first2=Gerry|title=Gays on the tube|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T2MEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA18&dq=%22running+for+honor%22&hl=en&ei=88WCTO7iOSTMngfO7qVX&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22running%20for%20honor%22&f=false|newspaper=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|page=12|date=August 20, 1996|accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1977 || ''[[All That Glitters (TV series)|All That Glitters]]'' || [[Broadcast syndication|Syndicated]] || Linda Murkland || [[Linda Gray]] || Linda Murkland was a transgender woman (the first transgender series regular on American television). {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1977\u20131981 || ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || [[Jodie Dallas]] || [[Billy Crystal]] || By the end of the series, Jodie was romantically involved with a woman. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1979\u20131981 || ''[[Agony (TV series)|Agony]]'' || [[ITV Network|ITV]] || Michael <br /> Rob || [[Peter Denyer]] <br /> [[Jeremy Bulloch]] || First British sitcom to feature a gay couple in a non-camp fashion.<ref>{{cite web|author=Admin|title=Remembering London Weekend Television \u2013 Part 3|url=http://www.britishclassiccomedy.co.uk/2013/04/maureen-lipman-in-agony/|website=British Classic Comedy|date=April 9, 2013|accessdate=22 July 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130417044021/http://www.britishclassiccomedy.co.uk/2013/04/maureen-lipman-in-agony/|archivedate=April 17, 2013|url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|} <!-- DO NOT REMOVE CLOSING MARKUP CODE -->\n\n==1980s==\n<!--Using Visual Editor: please be very careful when using VE. VE is problematic with tables. See [[WP:VE]] > Limitations-->\n<!--[[WP:VERIFY]]: \"All material in Wikipedia mainspace, including everything in articles, lists and captions, must be verifiable.\"-->\n<!--Please include citations from [[WP:RELIABLE]] sources that support addition of characters to this list.-->\n<!--If you are unsure of how to properly cite a source, open \"Cite\" on the [[Wikipedia:RefToolbar