[[Brothers (1984 TV series)|Brothers]]'' || [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] || Cliff Waters<br />Donald Maulpey || [[Paul Regina]]<br />[[Philip Charles MacKenzie]] || Two heterosexual brothers cope when third brother (Cliff) [[coming out|comes out]] as gay. Donald is Cliff's gay neighbor. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1985 || ''[[Sara (U.S. 1985 TV series)|Sara]]'' || [[NBC]] || Dennis Kemper || [[Bronson Pinchot]] || Dennis is an attorney in the law firm at which the series is set. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1987\u20131991 || ''[[Thirtysomething (TV series)|Thirtysomething]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || Russell Weller<br />Peter Montefiore|| [[David Marshall Grant]]<br />[[Peter Frechette]] || Two supporting gay characters, one an artist and one working in advertising. Focus of the episode [[Strangers (thirtysomething)|Strangers]]. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1987\u20131988 || ''[[Women in Prison (TV series)|Women in Prison]]'' || [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] || Bonnie Harper || [[Antoinette Byron]] || {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1987\u20131989 || ''[[Hooperman]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || Rick Silardi || Joseph Gian || Uniformed Police Officer Rick Silardi is openly gay, but seems to spend most of his time fending off the affections of his straight female police partner, Officer Mo DeMott ([[Sydney Walsh]]), who wants to \"save him\" from being gay by making passes at him whenever possible. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1988\u20131997 || ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || Bev Harris<br />Leon Carp<br />Scott<br />Nancy Bartlett|| [[Estelle Parsons]]<br />[[Martin Mull]]<br />[[Fred Willard]]<br />[[Sandra Bernhard]] || In the final episode, Rosanne Conner revealed that the last season was a story she'd written. Her mother wasn't really gay but her sister was. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1989\u20131991 || ''[[Doctor Doctor (1989 TV series)|Doctor Doctor]]'' || [[CBS]] || Richard Stratford || Tony Carreiro || Richard is the openly gay brother of lead character Mike Stratford ([[Matt Frewer]]). {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|} <!-- DO NOT REMOVE CLOSING MARKUP CODE -->\n\n==1990s==\n<!--Using Visual Editor: please be very careful when using VE. VE is problematic with tables. See [[WP:VE]] > Limitations-->\n<!--[[WP:VERIFY]]: \"All material in Wikipedia mainspace, including everything in articles, lists and captions, must be verifiable.\"-->\n<!--Please include citations from [[WP:RELIABLE]] sources that support addition of characters to this list.-->\n<!--If you are unsure of how to properly cite a source, open \"Cite\" on the [[Wikipedia:RefToolbar]] and select a Template. Click [Show/hide extra fields] button to open \"Date\" (i.e. date published), \"Archive\", and additional parameters.-->\n<!--LGBT characters are also listed by orientation in [[List of LGBT characters in television and radio]].-->\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margins:auto; width=100%;\"\n! style=\"width:75px;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:225px;\"|Show\n! style=\"width:100px\"|Network\n! style=\"width:200px\"|Character\n! style=\"width:200px\"|Actor\n! style=\"width:500px;\"|Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1990\u20131993 || ''[[You Rang M'Lord?]]'' || [[BBC]] || Helen Cooper Cecily \"Cissy\" Meldrum || [[Catherine Rabett]] || {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1990\u20131998 || ''[[Drop the Dead Donkey]]'' || [[Channel 4]] || Helen Cooper || [[Ingrid Lacey]] || {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1991\u20131997 || {{hs|Brittas Empire}}''[[The Brittas Empire]]'' || [[BBC]] || Gavin Featherly <br />Tim Whistler || [[Tim Marriott]]<br />[[Russell Porter (actor)|Russell Porter]] || Tim and Gavin are a couple working at the leisure centre, who, throughout, choose not to tell some people due to fear of being fired. Their homophobic boss is innocently oblivious to their relationship for seven years. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1992 || ''[[Terry and Julian]]'' || [[Channel 4]] || Julian || [[Julian Clary]] || {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1992\u20131998 || {{hs|Larry Sanders Show}}''[[The Larry Sanders Show]]'' || [[Home Box Office|HBO]] || Brian || [[Scott Thompson (comedian)|Scott Thompson]] || {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1993 || ''[[Cutters (TV series)|Cutters]]'' || [[CBS]] || Troy King || [[Julius Carry]] || Troy was an Olympic gold medalist turned hairdresser.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tropiano|first1=Stephen|title=The Prime Time Closet: A History of Gays and Lesbians on TV|date=2002|publisher=[[Applause Theatre & Cinema Books]]|isbn=978-1557835574 |url=https://archive.org/details/primetimecloseta00trop}} (p. 270)</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1993\u20131996 || ''[[The John Larroquette Show]]'' || [[NBC]] || Pat || [[Jazzmun]] || A [[drag queen]] who hangs out at the bus station where the lead character works. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1994 || ''[[Daddy's Girls (1994 TV series)|Daddy's Girls]]'' || [[CBS]] || Dennis Sinclair || [[Harvey Fierstein]] || Sinclair is a high-strung fashion designer. He was the first gay principal television character played by an openly gay actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1994-09-21-9409200450-story.html|title=DUDLEY DO WRONG: 'DADDY'S GIRLS' A SITCOM DUD|first=TOM|last=JICHA|date=|website=Sun-Sentinel.com}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1994\u20131998 || ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'' || [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] || Ellen Morgan <br /> Peter Barnes <br /> Barrett || [[Ellen DeGeneres]] <br /> [[Patrick Bristow]] <br /> [[Jack Plotnick]] || After months of media speculation, Ellen Morgan came out in \"[[The Puppy Episode]]\". Peter and Barrett were Ellen's friends and a couple. {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1994\u20131999 || {{hs|Vicar of Dibley}}''[[The Vicar of Dibley]]'' || [[BBC]] || Frank Pickle || [[John Bluthal]] || {{Citation needed|reason=Per WP:VERIFY \u2013 Verify sexual orientation of all characters.|date=June 2018}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1994\u20132004 || ''[[Friends]]'' || [[NBC]] || Carol Willick <br /> Susan Bunch || [[Jane Sibbett]] <br />[[Jessica Hecht]] || Carol is lesbian and Ross's ex-wife. <br /> Susan is lesbian and Carol's girlfriend. <br /> Carol and Susan married in season 2 episode \"[[The One with the Lesbian Wedding]]\". It was the first lesbian wedding portrayed on U.S. television.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gilchrist |first1=Tracy E. |title=5 Times Friends Was the Best Lesbian Show On TV |url=https://www.pride.com/television/2014/09/27/5-times-friends-was-best-lesbian-show-tv |website=[[Pride.com]] |date=September 27